1
00:03:31,720 --> 00:03:36,350
Seventeen dollars and 52 cents. That
settles my back taxes for '59 and '60.

2
00:03:36,520 --> 00:03:39,830
- That does it.
- Gougers, all of you. Gougers!

3
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:43,629
Don't tell it to me.
I make 60 bucks a week here.

4
00:03:44,200 --> 00:03:47,078
- Go ahead, lady. I can wait.
- LOUISA: Thank you.

5
00:03:47,480 --> 00:03:49,914
Is this where
you give the money in?

6
00:03:51,400 --> 00:03:54,517
Excuse me. Is this where
you give the money in?

7
00:03:57,640 --> 00:04:00,438
Let me see your form, miss.

8
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:03,114
I mean, did you make out a form?

9
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:05,555
I mean, where are your papers?

10
00:04:05,720 --> 00:04:08,439
Well, this is the only paper
that I thought was necessary.

11
00:04:08,600 --> 00:04:12,673
Oh, I can't take your check
without the regular 1040 form.

12
00:04:12,840 --> 00:04:16,594
It's to be sure it's the correct amount
according to your return.

13
00:04:16,760 --> 00:04:19,228
This isn't according to any return.
It's just money.

14
00:04:19,400 --> 00:04:22,915
- I wanna give it to the government.
- Well, this is very irregular.

15
00:04:23,080 --> 00:04:26,709
First of all, this is
the Department of Internal Revenue...

16
00:04:38,800 --> 00:04:41,678
Oh, I get it. April fool.

17
00:04:41,840 --> 00:04:44,718
- Next. Next.
- Oh, no. Please, I...

18
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:52,956
And then I went to see
the head clerk...

19
00:04:53,120 --> 00:04:56,635
...and then the assistant
to the secretary of Treasury...

20
00:04:56,800 --> 00:04:59,951
...and then
the secretary of Treasury.

21
00:05:00,120 --> 00:05:01,473
But...

22
00:05:01,640 --> 00:05:04,279
But when I insisted
on seeing the president...

23
00:05:04,440 --> 00:05:08,228
...well, they insisted
I come to see you.

24
00:05:08,440 --> 00:05:12,513
Dr. Svenson,
do you think I'm crazy too?

25
00:05:13,960 --> 00:05:18,158
The name is Steffanson.
Victor Steffanson.

26
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:21,312
And we never use that word
around here.

27
00:05:21,480 --> 00:05:26,031
Now, Mrs. Benson, you just take
one of these and try to relax.

28
00:05:26,920 --> 00:05:28,353
You know, Mrs...

29
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:29,555
[SCREAMS]

30
00:05:29,720 --> 00:05:31,358
Pink. Pink.

31
00:05:31,520 --> 00:05:33,954
They're pink pills.
My husband was pink.

32
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:37,795
- I can't take a pink pill.
- Crunch it. Crunch it right down.

33
00:05:37,960 --> 00:05:40,838
That's right. That's right.

34
00:05:41,840 --> 00:05:43,558
MOUTHS:
<i>Pink</i>.

35
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:45,392
[SOBBING]

36
00:05:46,360 --> 00:05:48,351
Mrs. Benson...

37
00:05:49,080 --> 00:05:52,755
...you are obviously the victim
of some inner disturbance...

38
00:05:52,960 --> 00:05:55,030
...which, well,
for want of a better word...

39
00:05:55,200 --> 00:05:58,192
...your guilts have led you
to a state of fantasy...

40
00:05:58,360 --> 00:06:03,673
...in which, A, you're burdened
with some fantastic wealth...

41
00:06:03,840 --> 00:06:06,718
...and B, you are eager
to rid yourself of it...

42
00:06:06,880 --> 00:06:12,034
...as in the ancient ritual of exorcising
some dybbuk or evil spirit.

43
00:06:12,200 --> 00:06:14,191
Now, now, now.
Now, this is normal.

44
00:06:14,360 --> 00:06:15,588
[BUZZING]

45
00:06:15,760 --> 00:06:17,512
Excuse me.

46
00:06:20,160 --> 00:06:23,835
Yes? Please don't... What?
Oh, yes, put him on.

47
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:25,479
Oh, hello, Fred.

48
00:06:25,640 --> 00:06:27,676
You investigated and...?

49
00:06:28,440 --> 00:06:30,078
Fred...

50
00:06:30,240 --> 00:06:31,832
The check is good?

51
00:06:34,920 --> 00:06:39,550
Uh-huh. Yes. Thank you, Fred.

52
00:06:41,160 --> 00:06:42,991
I have the strangest...

53
00:06:43,240 --> 00:06:45,390
...tingling sensation in my...

54
00:06:45,560 --> 00:06:47,312
In my toes.

55
00:06:49,200 --> 00:06:51,191
Are you all right?

56
00:06:51,360 --> 00:06:52,873
What?

57
00:06:53,600 --> 00:06:55,989
- Well, what happened?
- Well, A, you fainted...

58
00:06:56,160 --> 00:06:58,628
...and B, I poured water on you.
I'm terribly sorry...

59
00:06:58,800 --> 00:07:01,314
- ...but I didn't know what else to do.
- It's all right.

60
00:07:01,480 --> 00:07:03,675
You did the right thing.

61
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:08,156
- Do you faint often?
- Oh, just once in a while.

62
00:07:08,320 --> 00:07:09,719
It's the shock of realization...

63
00:07:09,880 --> 00:07:12,189
...whenever I've been dead wrong
about something.

64
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:13,839
The fainting is...

65
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:17,436
...running away, as it were,
from the reality that I'm not...

66
00:07:18,160 --> 00:07:20,355
I'm not infallible.

67
00:07:21,040 --> 00:07:25,113
You see, it's been the pattern
of my life from the time I was a...

68
00:07:25,560 --> 00:07:28,028
Wait a minute. What is this?

69
00:07:28,200 --> 00:07:31,272
Who is doing what to who?
Or whom?

70
00:07:31,440 --> 00:07:33,192
Mrs. Benson.

71
00:07:33,360 --> 00:07:36,511
You are a young woman who is
worth in the neighborhood...

72
00:07:36,680 --> 00:07:38,875
...of $200 million.

73
00:07:39,040 --> 00:07:42,191
And for some incredible reason,
you wanna give it to the government.

74
00:07:42,360 --> 00:07:45,079
You don't need a psychiatrist.
You need your head examined.

75
00:07:45,280 --> 00:07:47,316
- Now, out of my office.
- No, Dr. Steffanson...

76
00:07:47,480 --> 00:07:51,553
You said something a minute ago
that was very understanding and true.

77
00:07:51,720 --> 00:07:53,950
I never heard it expressed before.

78
00:07:54,120 --> 00:07:57,430
But I want your help.
Oh, please.

79
00:07:57,600 --> 00:07:59,158
Oh, yes.

80
00:07:59,560 --> 00:08:03,792
Yes, the oath I took forbids me
to turn away from a cry for help.

81
00:08:03,960 --> 00:08:06,155
Sit down, Mrs. Benson.

82
00:08:08,360 --> 00:08:11,318
It was what you said about
my wanting to get rid of my money.

83
00:08:11,480 --> 00:08:14,677
- Like exorcising some evil spirit.
- Yes.

84
00:08:14,840 --> 00:08:16,353
Dr. Steffanson...

85
00:08:16,520 --> 00:08:19,398
...I think I may be
some kind of a witch.

86
00:08:19,560 --> 00:08:22,279
Come, come now, Mrs. Benson.
This is the 19th cent...

87
00:08:22,440 --> 00:08:23,919
- Twentieth century.
- No, really.

88
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:27,390
Every man whose life I touch withers.

89
00:08:28,200 --> 00:08:29,713
Really?

90
00:08:32,200 --> 00:08:36,432
Mrs. Benson, please just turn over
and try to relax.

91
00:08:39,520 --> 00:08:41,556
Go right ahead now.

92
00:08:42,960 --> 00:08:44,598
Well...

93
00:08:44,840 --> 00:08:47,559
...I was born Louisa May Foster...

94
00:08:47,720 --> 00:08:50,951
...in the small town
of Crawleyville, Ohio.

95
00:08:51,120 --> 00:08:54,430
Oh, I can't understand it.
I never wanted money.

96
00:08:54,600 --> 00:08:57,592
All I ever wanted
was to lead a simple life...

97
00:08:57,760 --> 00:09:00,832
...with one man to love
and to love me.

98
00:09:01,240 --> 00:09:04,073
A simple life somewhere
in a little cottage.

99
00:09:04,240 --> 00:09:05,673
That's all I ever wanted...

100
00:09:05,840 --> 00:09:08,559
...ever since I was a little girl
with my mother and father.

101
00:09:08,720 --> 00:09:10,950
STEFFANSON: Oh, your mother.
What was your mother like?

102
00:09:11,120 --> 00:09:12,633
Mother?

103
00:09:13,040 --> 00:09:15,235
Well, Mother kept Daddy
and me clean.

104
00:09:15,400 --> 00:09:18,312
<i>Neat as a pin,</i>
<i>and took us to church every Sunday</i>.

105
00:09:18,480 --> 00:09:19,913
PRIEST:
So now I say unto you:

106
00:09:20,120 --> 00:09:22,554
Love thy neighbor as thyself.

107
00:09:22,760 --> 00:09:25,354
'Tis better to give than to receive.

108
00:09:25,560 --> 00:09:29,917
Money is the root of all evil.

109
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:33,112
LOUISA: <i>Mother even had embroidered</i>
<i>these very sentiments on samplers</i>...

110
00:09:33,280 --> 00:09:35,475
...<i>for our living room at home</i>.

111
00:09:35,760 --> 00:09:39,435
<i>But we were poor, and Mother found it</i>
<i>hard to live up to these ideas</i>.

112
00:09:39,600 --> 00:09:41,716
MRS. FOSTER:
Good day, Mrs. Jenkins.

113
00:09:41,880 --> 00:09:46,874
Sherman. Did you see Emily Jenkins,
that slob smothered in a mink cape?

114
00:09:47,040 --> 00:09:49,429
I hate her guts.

115
00:09:49,600 --> 00:09:50,919
"Look what I've got".

116
00:09:51,320 --> 00:09:53,709
Her husband was a shipping clerk
15 years ago.

117
00:09:53,880 --> 00:09:56,075
Same as you. Now look at him.
Look at you.

118
00:09:56,280 --> 00:09:58,191
Where's your drive?
Where's your ambition?

119
00:09:58,360 --> 00:10:01,477
That's what counts in this world.
Success. Money.

120
00:10:01,640 --> 00:10:05,952
Success. Money.
President of the Nice Fellows Club.

121
00:10:06,120 --> 00:10:07,872
Oh.

122
00:10:09,840 --> 00:10:12,638
LOUISA [MIMICKING MOTHER]: <i>"Money</i>.
<i>Success. Get to the top. Money</i>.

123
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:15,553
<i>Success. Money. Money. Money. "</i>

124
00:10:20,360 --> 00:10:23,397
LOUISA [IN NORMAL VOICE]: <i>As the</i>
<i>years went by, I saw my sweet daddy</i>...

125
00:10:23,560 --> 00:10:25,118
...<i>dwindle away under this</i>...

126
00:10:25,280 --> 00:10:28,238
...<i>till you practically</i>
<i>didn't know he was there</i>.

127
00:10:29,400 --> 00:10:32,915
<i>I began to understand what Mother</i>
<i>really meant by those samplers</i>.

128
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:44,397
You play your cards right, and we'll
have more money than we need.

129
00:10:44,560 --> 00:10:47,996
But, Mother, money isn't everything.

130
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:50,435
I know Leonard Crawley
owns Crawley's Emporium...

131
00:10:50,600 --> 00:10:53,068
...and three-quarters
of the property in Crawleyville.

132
00:10:53,240 --> 00:10:56,676
But I'm not gonna marry him just
because he's the richest man in town.

133
00:10:56,840 --> 00:11:00,116
He's a sneak and a bore and a drag...

134
00:11:00,280 --> 00:11:02,271
...and he's been with every girl
there is...

135
00:11:02,440 --> 00:11:03,998
...and besides, I don't love him.

136
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:07,118
- There's no such thing as love.
- He's a snob.

137
00:11:07,280 --> 00:11:09,919
He's ashamed of you
and where we live.

138
00:11:10,080 --> 00:11:13,152
Why he won't even walk in this house
when he comes to call for me.

139
00:11:13,320 --> 00:11:16,153
I wouldn't come in here either
if I didn't have to.

140
00:11:16,320 --> 00:11:19,118
Louisa, you turned out real beautiful.

141
00:11:19,280 --> 00:11:23,796
You have something to sell.
Take a mother's advice. Sell it now.

142
00:11:24,560 --> 00:11:26,278
[CAR HORN HONKING]

143
00:11:26,800 --> 00:11:29,598
- There's Leonard. You better hurry.
- I'm not going.

144
00:11:29,760 --> 00:11:33,116
How dare you turn down a man
like Leonard Crawley?

145
00:11:33,280 --> 00:11:36,033
I tell you, he has money.
You go and get it.

146
00:11:39,320 --> 00:11:40,719
LOUISA:
<i>Leonard was waiting</i>.

147
00:11:40,880 --> 00:11:43,110
<i>I thought over everything</i>
<i>he had to offer</i>.

148
00:11:43,360 --> 00:11:46,591
<i>The Crawley home,</i>
<i>the Crawley stables</i>...

149
00:11:46,880 --> 00:11:48,552
...<i>Crawley's department store</i>.

150
00:11:48,880 --> 00:11:51,599
<i>But then</i>
<i>there was Leonard himself</i>.

151
00:11:53,120 --> 00:11:55,918
<i>Leonard Crawley was a</i>...

152
00:11:56,880 --> 00:11:59,030
<i>Hm, how shall I say it?</i>

153
00:12:00,200 --> 00:12:01,997
<i>Well, that's not fair, I guess</i>.

154
00:12:02,160 --> 00:12:03,991
<i>He was just Leonard Crawley,</i>
<i>son of wealth</i>.

155
00:12:04,560 --> 00:12:06,710
Put it down right down
next to mine, baby.

156
00:12:06,880 --> 00:12:08,313
Gee, I wish I'd said that.

157
00:12:08,480 --> 00:12:12,268
LENNY: Oh, you can use it any time
you want. Just give credit to Crawley.

158
00:12:12,440 --> 00:12:15,989
That's more than Crawley ever did
for anyone else in this town.

159
00:12:18,360 --> 00:12:22,273
Oh, by the way, you let your mom know
the payment's due on her refrigerator.

160
00:12:22,440 --> 00:12:25,637
Don't give her the idea that us
getting married gets her off the hook.

161
00:12:25,800 --> 00:12:27,313
Oh, no.

162
00:12:27,520 --> 00:12:29,351
She couldn't be your real mother.

163
00:12:29,520 --> 00:12:32,557
She must have been left on your
front doorstep one stormy night...

164
00:12:32,720 --> 00:12:34,233
...in a cage.

165
00:12:34,400 --> 00:12:37,551
Why are you so intent on marrying me
when it's perfectly obvious...

166
00:12:37,720 --> 00:12:40,280
...I'm indifferent to you
and all the so-called advantages...

167
00:12:40,440 --> 00:12:42,510
- ...you have to offer me?
- That's just it.

168
00:12:42,680 --> 00:12:45,752
You're the only girl in town who
doesn't throw herself at me...

169
00:12:45,920 --> 00:12:49,469
...and scream, "Take me, take me".
You know, you suggest good breeding.

170
00:12:49,640 --> 00:12:51,437
Heaven knows where you got it from.

171
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:53,955
But also, you'll produce me an heir...

172
00:12:54,120 --> 00:12:56,156
...and then my mother
will stop nagging me...

173
00:12:56,320 --> 00:12:58,436
...about carrying on
the Crawley tradition.

174
00:12:58,600 --> 00:13:01,910
Any better reason than that
for getting married?

175
00:13:03,040 --> 00:13:05,156
- How about love?
- Love?

176
00:13:05,320 --> 00:13:07,231
Well, let me put it this way, honey:

177
00:13:07,400 --> 00:13:09,789
I'm very rich
and you're very poor...

178
00:13:09,960 --> 00:13:12,952
...and sooner or later
you're gonna come around.

179
00:13:13,880 --> 00:13:16,599
- You know the indifference I felt?
- Hm?

180
00:13:17,760 --> 00:13:19,796
Well, it's beginning to change.

181
00:13:19,960 --> 00:13:23,839
It's beginning to blossom
into complete contempt.

182
00:13:24,840 --> 00:13:26,114
What did I tell you, honey?

183
00:13:26,280 --> 00:13:28,953
I told you you were gonna
come around sooner or later.

184
00:13:35,960 --> 00:13:39,509
Gotta pick up the 6:00 town news
from my store manager.

185
00:13:39,680 --> 00:13:42,638
- The Crawley gestapo.
- Oh, yes.

186
00:13:42,800 --> 00:13:44,233
[HORN HONKS]

187
00:13:45,440 --> 00:13:47,510
Uh-oh, that eyesore.

188
00:13:47,680 --> 00:13:49,557
The only spot in town
we don't own.

189
00:13:49,760 --> 00:13:53,958
But it's just a matter of time
before old Hopper will come around.

190
00:13:54,720 --> 00:13:57,314
Just like you, baby.

191
00:13:59,880 --> 00:14:01,711
Good afternoon, Mr. Crawley,
Miss Foster.

192
00:14:01,880 --> 00:14:04,155
- Nice spring weather...
- Make it fast, Driscoll.

193
00:14:04,320 --> 00:14:07,869
Mrs. Willoughby was five minutes late
getting back from the doctor today.

194
00:14:08,040 --> 00:14:10,110
- Five dollars' fine off her salary.
- Yes, sir.

195
00:14:10,440 --> 00:14:13,318
Hopper sent back the answer
to your latest bid on his property.

196
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:16,159
It's still no. He says he doesn't
want to make money.

197
00:14:16,320 --> 00:14:18,754
He just wants to keep
his little place as it is.

198
00:14:18,920 --> 00:14:22,959
Edgar Hopper. I haven't run into him
since high school.

199
00:14:24,760 --> 00:14:28,309
Hm, I wonder how many days
I'd get for manslaughter.

200
00:14:28,480 --> 00:14:31,790
In Crawleyville, they wouldn't
even fine you, sir.

201
00:14:31,960 --> 00:14:33,473
[CAR STARTS]

202
00:14:50,520 --> 00:14:53,239
- EDGAR: Hi, Lenny.
- Edgar, better watch where you're going.

203
00:14:53,400 --> 00:14:55,834
Yeah, you're right, Lenny.
I was looking at the sun.

204
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:58,070
- Aren't you angry?
- Why should I be angry?

205
00:14:58,240 --> 00:15:00,310
- It was my fault.
- Then maybe we could fight.

206
00:15:00,480 --> 00:15:02,789
No sense doing that.
You'd kick the heck out of me.

207
00:15:02,960 --> 00:15:05,679
All that football and golf
and tennis and everything.

208
00:15:05,840 --> 00:15:07,592
You're a real winner, Lenny.

209
00:15:07,760 --> 00:15:09,273
What are you, an orthodox coward?

210
00:15:09,440 --> 00:15:12,034
No, Lenny, I just believe
in passive resistance.

211
00:15:12,200 --> 00:15:14,316
LENNY:
Oh, Mahatma Hopper, I presume.

212
00:15:14,480 --> 00:15:17,199
As a matter of fact, Gandhi
and I both got it from this guy.

213
00:15:17,360 --> 00:15:21,035
- Henry Thoreau.
- You're all covered with mud, Edgar.

214
00:15:21,360 --> 00:15:22,998
I mean, Mr. Hopper.

215
00:15:23,840 --> 00:15:26,638
Louisa... Louisa Foster, isn't it?

216
00:15:26,840 --> 00:15:29,149
I haven't seen you
since Mrs. Pritchard's class.

217
00:15:29,320 --> 00:15:31,276
Hey, you've grown.
Or maybe I shrunk.

218
00:15:31,440 --> 00:15:34,193
He wouldn't be covered with
this mud if he'd let the town...

219
00:15:34,360 --> 00:15:37,193
...pave that road in front
of his property like anybody else.

220
00:15:37,360 --> 00:15:40,477
It costs too much, Lenny. For what
you charge for a bag of cement...

221
00:15:40,640 --> 00:15:42,835
...this town ought to be
paved with gold.

222
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:45,116
Thanks, Lenny.
Hey, I gotta be going.

223
00:15:45,280 --> 00:15:48,317
I don't wanna keep those trout waiting.
See you.

224
00:15:48,720 --> 00:15:52,395
Don't grow any more, Miss Foster.
You're just right now.

225
00:15:52,560 --> 00:15:54,915
- Goodbye.
- Bye.

226
00:16:00,120 --> 00:16:01,519
[CAR HORN HONKS]

227
00:16:21,200 --> 00:16:22,758
[SPLASHING]

228
00:16:23,680 --> 00:16:27,195
- Hello.
- Hello. Imagine finding you here.

229
00:16:27,360 --> 00:16:31,273
- I just happened to be swimming by.
- Well, you scared the fish away.

230
00:16:31,440 --> 00:16:35,911
You can pull me in. I am full-grown.
You said so yourself.

231
00:16:36,080 --> 00:16:37,593
Thank you.

232
00:16:37,760 --> 00:16:39,352
Sit down.

233
00:16:40,080 --> 00:16:42,355
Here, put this on.

234
00:16:42,520 --> 00:16:44,511
Thanks. Did you catch any?

235
00:16:44,680 --> 00:16:47,319
Well, yeah. Three, including you.

236
00:16:47,480 --> 00:16:50,631
I'll cook them for you.
My clothes are right down there.

237
00:16:50,800 --> 00:16:52,756
Do you have anything
to cook them in?

238
00:16:52,920 --> 00:16:56,390
Well, my baronial estate's
right over there.

239
00:16:56,560 --> 00:16:59,632
- Is that where you live?
- Yeah, I...

240
00:17:00,080 --> 00:17:02,640
It's on the simple side,
I know.

241
00:17:02,840 --> 00:17:05,229
Simple. Yes.

242
00:17:05,400 --> 00:17:08,836
"Our lives are frittered away
by detail.

243
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:11,833
Simplify. Simplify".

244
00:17:12,200 --> 00:17:13,553
What did you say?

245
00:17:14,240 --> 00:17:17,994
- "Our lives are frittered away by detail.
- "By detail.

246
00:17:18,160 --> 00:17:20,628
- Simplify, simplify".
- Simplify, simplify".

247
00:17:21,400 --> 00:17:22,958
A girl who can quote Thoreau.

248
00:17:23,360 --> 00:17:26,238
I couldn't quote him before
I went to the library this morning.

249
00:17:26,400 --> 00:17:29,358
I'd never even heard of him
before yesterday.

250
00:17:29,520 --> 00:17:33,593
You mean, you didn't swim
by my boat just by accident?

251
00:17:34,920 --> 00:17:36,353
No.

252
00:17:37,520 --> 00:17:39,158
Gee.

253
00:17:56,720 --> 00:18:00,190
EDGAR: What is the future Mrs. Leonard
Crawley doing here anyway?

254
00:18:00,360 --> 00:18:02,316
LOUISA: Now, whatever gave you
that idea about me?

255
00:18:02,840 --> 00:18:06,913
Well, I don't know. Everybody
in town takes it for granted.

256
00:18:07,080 --> 00:18:11,198
- You are engaged to him, aren't you?
- Well, he takes it for granted.

257
00:18:12,760 --> 00:18:14,591
But, Edgar...

258
00:18:15,480 --> 00:18:18,153
...as far back as I can remember...

259
00:18:18,320 --> 00:18:20,595
...in grammar school,
in Mrs. Pritchard's class...

260
00:18:20,760 --> 00:18:22,591
You know,
when I sat in front of you?

261
00:18:22,760 --> 00:18:25,479
I wished that I had had
long pigtails...

262
00:18:25,640 --> 00:18:27,596
...so you could stick them
in the inkwell.

263
00:18:27,760 --> 00:18:31,355
- Did you really?
- I'm not gonna marry Leonard Crawley.

264
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:34,990
Of course, he'll never understand
anyone turning him down.

265
00:18:35,840 --> 00:18:37,159
Especially for you.

266
00:18:38,360 --> 00:18:40,271
Louisa.

267
00:18:41,680 --> 00:18:43,875
You mean, you'd take this...

268
00:18:44,040 --> 00:18:46,076
...instead of all that?

269
00:18:46,240 --> 00:18:49,232
But, Louisa, I've got nothing.

270
00:18:49,400 --> 00:18:51,868
I'll always have nothing.
I'll always be nothing.

271
00:18:52,280 --> 00:18:55,909
But, Edgar, that's what I want.
Nothing.

272
00:18:56,080 --> 00:18:58,469
To quote me and not Thoreau...

273
00:18:58,640 --> 00:19:00,437
...I love you.

274
00:19:09,320 --> 00:19:11,117
Oh, Louisa.

275
00:19:11,280 --> 00:19:12,918
I'll make you happy.

276
00:19:13,080 --> 00:19:14,957
I'll never work hard.

277
00:19:15,120 --> 00:19:18,317
I'll never make good. I swear it.

278
00:19:20,160 --> 00:19:22,879
It's true, Mother.
I've married Edgar Hopper.

279
00:19:23,040 --> 00:19:24,268
[SCREAMING]

280
00:19:28,320 --> 00:19:31,232
LOUISA: <i>Whereas Mother received</i>
<i>the news of my marriage to Edgar</i>...

281
00:19:31,400 --> 00:19:33,356
...<i>with ill-disguised displeasure</i>...

282
00:19:33,560 --> 00:19:36,552
...<i>Leonard took the news in his stride</i>.

283
00:19:45,280 --> 00:19:48,750
<i>For a while, Edgar and I</i>
<i>led an idyllic life</i>.

284
00:19:48,920 --> 00:19:51,275
<i>He went off to the store</i>
<i>a couple of hours a week</i>.

285
00:19:51,440 --> 00:19:53,590
<i>But the rest of the time</i>
<i>belonged to us</i>.

286
00:19:53,760 --> 00:19:56,115
<i>As I look back on it,</i>
<i>I see our life together</i>...

287
00:19:56,280 --> 00:19:58,396
...<i>as a wonderful, old silent movie</i>.

288
00:21:48,200 --> 00:21:50,919
Oh, I'll have this leak fixed
in no time.

289
00:21:51,080 --> 00:21:53,674
Well, that old water tank
always gave a lot of trouble.

290
00:21:53,840 --> 00:21:57,071
I'm going to the store and get
some chicken wire and fix these springs.

291
00:21:57,240 --> 00:21:59,071
You can do anything
with chicken wire.

292
00:21:59,240 --> 00:22:01,595
- I sure do love chicken wire.
- EDGAR: Leonard.

293
00:22:01,760 --> 00:22:04,718
If you're thinking of making dinner,
I'd be pleased to stay.

294
00:22:04,880 --> 00:22:06,199
- LOUISA: Hello, Leonard.
- Hi.

295
00:22:06,360 --> 00:22:08,874
Well, if it isn't the happy Hoppers
at home.

296
00:22:09,040 --> 00:22:12,919
This is the first chance I've had
to come over and see you lovebirds.

297
00:22:13,080 --> 00:22:15,196
I saw the Taj Mahal
by moonlight, Louisa.

298
00:22:15,360 --> 00:22:17,669
Oh, but I envy you here.

299
00:22:17,840 --> 00:22:20,638
- What's that camera for?
- Oh, I'm doing a documentary:

300
00:22:20,800 --> 00:22:23,678
<i>Slum Conditions in Crawleyville</i>.

301
00:22:24,040 --> 00:22:27,271
Oh, come now, Leonard.
You needn't be such a sore loser.

302
00:22:27,440 --> 00:22:31,433
Well, you gave me up for all this,
and I can understand it.

303
00:22:31,600 --> 00:22:35,479
You know, a nice roof under your feet,
rain a-face at night...

304
00:22:35,640 --> 00:22:37,631
...all the grass you can eat.

305
00:22:37,800 --> 00:22:39,074
EDGAR:
Hey, Leonard.

306
00:22:39,240 --> 00:22:41,959
Get out of here before
I twist your head off like a turnip.

307
00:22:42,120 --> 00:22:44,873
Well, is this the voice
of passive resistance speaking?

308
00:22:45,040 --> 00:22:46,393
No. Just get out of here.

309
00:22:46,560 --> 00:22:48,039
[SCREAMING]

310
00:22:48,840 --> 00:22:51,229
Oh, Louisa. You all right?

311
00:22:54,160 --> 00:22:57,675
LENNY: Well, another innovation
for modern living, huh?

312
00:22:57,840 --> 00:22:59,956
Instant shower for milady.

313
00:23:00,120 --> 00:23:02,839
- There. Well...
- I'm afraid I'm not a bit handy, Edgar.

314
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:04,319
LENNY:
Oh, no, but you are handy.

315
00:23:04,480 --> 00:23:06,755
I could use you down at the store
doing odd jobs.

316
00:23:06,920 --> 00:23:08,717
I'd pay you. You could earn a living.

317
00:23:08,880 --> 00:23:12,156
My wife doesn't have to work.
I'm sorry.

318
00:23:15,880 --> 00:23:17,916
Ed, seriously, Ed,
why don't you come down...

319
00:23:18,080 --> 00:23:21,311
...and see me this afternoon,
sell me that piece of property of yours?

320
00:23:21,480 --> 00:23:24,916
Someone could do something with it.
Not you, of course, but someone.

321
00:23:25,080 --> 00:23:26,718
- I said, get out of here.
- LENNY: All right.

322
00:23:26,880 --> 00:23:28,791
- Get out of here.
- All right, I will.

323
00:23:28,960 --> 00:23:33,351
Sorry to have barged in on you kids,
but I'll send a Christmas basket.

324
00:23:43,800 --> 00:23:47,634
- What's the matter, darling?
- Oh, nothing.

325
00:23:48,160 --> 00:23:50,958
I think I'll go down to the store
for a while this afternoon.

326
00:23:51,120 --> 00:23:53,395
But you were there
just 10 days ago.

327
00:23:53,560 --> 00:23:58,998
Well, it's got that chicken wire
I want and some nails.

328
00:23:59,240 --> 00:24:00,673
You know...

329
00:24:00,880 --> 00:24:03,155
...it's the end of summer.
People are coming home.

330
00:24:03,320 --> 00:24:05,038
Somebody might want something.

331
00:24:05,600 --> 00:24:07,795
Well, I'll be back.

332
00:24:11,520 --> 00:24:14,034
LOUISA:
<i>But he never really did come back</i>.

333
00:24:14,200 --> 00:24:16,270
<i>Not the Edgar Hopper I knew</i>.

334
00:24:17,600 --> 00:24:20,592
<i>When he hadn't returned</i>
<i>by the next day, I hurried into town</i>.

335
00:24:20,760 --> 00:24:23,797
EDGAR: Hop to Hopper's! The lowest
prices in town. Unlimited credit.

336
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:26,594
This is the biggest sale
in the history of our county.

337
00:24:26,760 --> 00:24:29,320
Don't crawl to Crawley's, folks.
Hop, hop to Hopper's.

338
00:24:29,480 --> 00:24:32,552
I guarantee you 10 percent off
because there's no air conditioning.

339
00:24:32,720 --> 00:24:34,472
This is it.
Right here on Main Street.

340
00:24:34,640 --> 00:24:37,154
Hop, hop to Hopper's.
We undersell everybody.

341
00:24:37,320 --> 00:24:40,232
Come right in, folks. Instant credit.
If we haven't got it...

342
00:24:40,400 --> 00:24:42,834
...we'll get it for you.
Don't crawl to Crawley's.

343
00:24:43,040 --> 00:24:45,634
Hop, hop to Hopper's.
So all you shoppers...

344
00:24:45,800 --> 00:24:47,597
Louisa.

345
00:24:49,520 --> 00:24:52,080
- What is all this?
- Hopper's Taj Mahal, honey.

346
00:24:52,240 --> 00:24:54,708
And it's all for you.
Listen, Louisa, when that...

347
00:24:54,880 --> 00:24:57,394
...snake rattled into our house,
something snapped.

348
00:24:57,640 --> 00:24:59,756
Where have you been?
Why didn't you come home?

349
00:24:59,920 --> 00:25:03,151
There you were, mending the roof.
My wife.

350
00:25:03,320 --> 00:25:06,278
Hop, hop, hop, you shoppers.
Hop to Hopper's.

351
00:25:06,440 --> 00:25:07,998
Honey, I wanna get you things.

352
00:25:08,160 --> 00:25:10,799
Dresses and things for the house.
A house.

353
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:13,639
- But I like our house.
- What is it that makes a family...

354
00:25:13,800 --> 00:25:17,156
...go to the same store over and over
and no place else?

355
00:25:17,600 --> 00:25:20,876
I don't know. Free eats.
Free toys for the kiddies?

356
00:25:21,040 --> 00:25:24,715
That's it. We'll stuff them
and then we'll sell them.

357
00:25:24,880 --> 00:25:28,190
Hop, hop, hop, you shoppers.
Hop, hop, hop to Hopper's.

358
00:25:28,360 --> 00:25:30,157
Come on, honey.
Let me show you around.

359
00:25:30,800 --> 00:25:32,552
Hey, you kids.
Get up on top there.

360
00:25:32,720 --> 00:25:34,631
Keep with the,
"Hop, hop, hop to Hopper's".

361
00:25:34,800 --> 00:25:36,279
- This is wonderful.
- Oh, thanks.

362
00:25:36,440 --> 00:25:37,839
- Terrific.
- Thanks for coming.

363
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:39,513
There's a lot more bargains here.

364
00:25:39,680 --> 00:25:42,319
MAN 1: We'll be back, Eddie.
MAN 2: Some bargains, Eddie.

365
00:25:42,480 --> 00:25:43,879
- Congratulations.
- Thanks.

366
00:25:44,080 --> 00:25:47,709
Prices are low, the goods are right,
come to Hopper's from morn till night.

367
00:25:47,880 --> 00:25:49,677
We're open till 10:00 every night.

368
00:25:49,840 --> 00:25:51,068
- How's it going?
- MAN 3: Oh, great.

369
00:25:51,240 --> 00:25:53,435
- Good to hear it. Those are on sale.
- Edgar.

370
00:25:53,600 --> 00:25:55,556
When will we ever see each other?

371
00:25:55,720 --> 00:25:59,429
As soon as this thing gets going,
we'll have more time together than ever.

372
00:25:59,600 --> 00:26:01,670
But we had all our time
together before.

373
00:26:01,840 --> 00:26:03,751
- What about Thoreau?
- Thoreau?

374
00:26:03,920 --> 00:26:06,115
But you don't want to keep pace
like the others.

375
00:26:06,280 --> 00:26:07,952
You heard a different drummer.

376
00:26:08,160 --> 00:26:09,912
Oh, yeah.
I hear a different drummer.

377
00:26:10,080 --> 00:26:14,710
And the music I hear says,
"Hop, hop, Eddie. Hop, hop".

378
00:26:17,160 --> 00:26:19,674
Well, looks like we've got him
at last, Driscoll.

379
00:26:19,840 --> 00:26:22,229
Have we?
The people seem to be eating it up.

380
00:26:22,440 --> 00:26:24,351
LENNY:
Anybody will run to look at a freak.

381
00:26:24,760 --> 00:26:28,639
I figure I'll give him three months, and
he'll hop himself right into oblivion.

382
00:26:28,800 --> 00:26:31,314
BO Y:
Hop, hop, hop to Hoppers!

383
00:26:31,480 --> 00:26:33,038
Hop, hop, hop to Hopper's!

384
00:26:33,200 --> 00:26:35,714
Hop, hop, hop to Hopper's. Hop...

385
00:26:36,400 --> 00:26:39,551
Forgive me, sir.
But we really must advertise.

386
00:26:39,760 --> 00:26:42,593
We must, huh? You're fired.

387
00:26:44,160 --> 00:26:47,948
HOPPER: Merry Christmas.
And a hop, hop, hoppy New Year.

388
00:26:49,040 --> 00:26:53,591
Merry Christmas.
And a hop, hop, hoppy New Year.

389
00:26:55,440 --> 00:26:57,874
MRS. FREEMAN: I bought a lot.
HOPPER: You bought out the store.

390
00:26:58,040 --> 00:27:00,429
And it's no trouble at all,
Mrs. Freeman. No trouble.

391
00:27:00,600 --> 00:27:02,352
You can't leave, we leave with you.

392
00:27:02,520 --> 00:27:06,274
Hey, Ned, you drop Mrs. Freeman off
on her way home, okay?

393
00:27:06,800 --> 00:27:10,076
Oh, thank you, Edgar.
And merry Christmas.

394
00:27:10,240 --> 00:27:11,753
- LOUISA: Edgar.
- Be right with you, lady.

395
00:27:11,920 --> 00:27:15,151
- Merry Christmas to you, Mrs. Freeman.
- Edgar.

396
00:27:15,320 --> 00:27:17,675
Oh, hi, honey. Excuse me,
I gotta get back.

397
00:27:17,840 --> 00:27:20,149
But, Edgar,
aren't you coming home soon?

398
00:27:20,320 --> 00:27:22,595
I'm sorry, we're staying open
till midnight.

399
00:27:22,760 --> 00:27:24,239
What's the matter?

400
00:27:24,400 --> 00:27:27,119
Nothing. I'm just a little lonely,
that's all.

401
00:27:27,280 --> 00:27:29,396
What? In that big, beautiful new house?
Lonely?

402
00:27:30,040 --> 00:27:32,679
I'm the only one who's ever in it.

403
00:27:32,840 --> 00:27:35,115
Edgar, it's Christmas.

404
00:27:35,320 --> 00:27:37,834
But, yes, and Christmas is business.
Big business.

405
00:27:38,600 --> 00:27:40,875
You're working entirely too hard,
darling.

406
00:27:41,040 --> 00:27:44,635
By this time next year, we'll be so rich
we can take a real vacation.

407
00:27:44,800 --> 00:27:46,438
- Italy?
- Italy.

408
00:27:46,600 --> 00:27:47,874
MAN:
Merry Christmas.

409
00:27:48,040 --> 00:27:50,759
What's the matter with work?
Hard work never killed anybody.

410
00:27:50,920 --> 00:27:52,592
- MAN: Merry Christmas.
- Hi there.

411
00:27:52,760 --> 00:27:55,069
MAN:
And a hop, hop, hoppy New Year.

412
00:28:06,280 --> 00:28:08,316
LOUISA: <i>Edgar's hard work</i>
<i>included hitting out</i>...

413
00:28:08,520 --> 00:28:11,318
...<i>with every modern sales device</i>
<i>known to man</i>.

414
00:28:11,480 --> 00:28:13,550
<i>And Crawleyville</i>
<i>was his captive audience</i>.

415
00:28:13,760 --> 00:28:15,239
<i>We were millionaires overnight</i>.

416
00:28:15,800 --> 00:28:17,995
Darling, I've checked
the hotels in Rome...

417
00:28:18,160 --> 00:28:20,390
...and I have the reservations
for our vacation.

418
00:28:20,560 --> 00:28:22,915
I'm sorry, that'll have to wait
till next year.

419
00:28:23,080 --> 00:28:25,036
- Next year?
- Yes, next year.

420
00:28:25,200 --> 00:28:29,113
In the meantime, get a couple
of art books and a box of spaghetti.

421
00:28:29,880 --> 00:28:32,075
You liar. You cheat!

422
00:28:32,240 --> 00:28:34,549
- You deceived me.
- Deceived you?

423
00:28:34,720 --> 00:28:37,234
You think I've got a blond tootsie
on the side?

424
00:28:37,400 --> 00:28:39,152
Oh, I just wish you had!

425
00:28:39,320 --> 00:28:42,471
At least then
I'd know you were relaxing!

426
00:28:46,520 --> 00:28:49,557
You don't even have any feelings
anymore.

427
00:28:49,720 --> 00:28:52,314
When we got married,
you promised for better or worse...

428
00:28:52,480 --> 00:28:55,199
...that you'd never make good.
That you'd always be nothing.

429
00:28:55,360 --> 00:28:58,750
Well, look at us. We're so rich we
never even see each other anymore.

430
00:28:58,920 --> 00:29:01,514
Edgar, you're " frittering away
your life in detail.

431
00:29:01,760 --> 00:29:03,591
Simplify. Simplify".

432
00:29:03,760 --> 00:29:08,311
Simplify, "schmimplify".
A little hard work never killed anybody.

433
00:29:08,960 --> 00:29:10,712
LOUISA:
<i>Edgar was like someone bewitched</i>.

434
00:29:10,880 --> 00:29:13,474
<i>Like the Sorcerer's Apprentice,</i>
<i>he couldn't stop</i>.

435
00:29:13,640 --> 00:29:15,835
Get me 300,000 feet
of rust-proof chicken wire.

436
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:20,198
What is with our order on the
Mother Goose Atomic Disintegrator Kit?

437
00:29:20,720 --> 00:29:23,837
Make them think they can't live
without door knobs that light up.

438
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:25,035
Think big.

439
00:29:25,200 --> 00:29:27,919
Our musical mop, which plays
"Let Me Call You Sweetheart"...

440
00:29:28,080 --> 00:29:30,196
...is a failure.
Get something happier...

441
00:29:30,360 --> 00:29:33,352
...like "Stars and Stripes Forever"
to guarantee musical mop-up.

442
00:29:33,560 --> 00:29:35,551
So it is just a simple equation:

443
00:29:35,720 --> 00:29:39,474
Service quotient X plus
condensation-atmosphere quotient Y...

444
00:29:39,640 --> 00:29:41,710
...plus smile-and-affability
quotient X...

445
00:29:41,880 --> 00:29:44,269
...show in the last three months
a sales gain line...

446
00:29:44,440 --> 00:29:46,715
...that has hop, hopped right off
the lousy board.

447
00:29:46,880 --> 00:29:49,269
In short, boys, we are becoming,
by the figures...

448
00:29:49,440 --> 00:29:52,398
...the big, bigger, biggest.

449
00:29:55,320 --> 00:29:58,756
In re yours of the 23rd,
I am impatiently awaiting your order.

450
00:29:58,920 --> 00:30:00,353
Hastily yours, Edgar Hopper.

451
00:30:00,520 --> 00:30:02,909
There can be no delays.
If you insist on delaying...

452
00:30:03,080 --> 00:30:05,674
...you can be replaced.
Hastily yours, Edgar Hopper.

453
00:30:05,840 --> 00:30:09,196
Since your delivery service isn't quick,
we're terminating our agreement.

454
00:30:09,360 --> 00:30:11,191
Hastily yours, Edgar Hopper.

455
00:30:11,360 --> 00:30:14,477
I'd like all those folders rushed out
to the mailing list by Monday.

456
00:30:14,640 --> 00:30:16,551
Hastily yours, Edgar Hopper.
Order cancelled.

457
00:30:16,720 --> 00:30:18,551
We asked for goods,
you gave us promises.

458
00:30:18,720 --> 00:30:20,517
Hastily yours, Edgar Hopper.

459
00:30:20,680 --> 00:30:23,911
All displays in the branch stores
must be changed daily and rotated.

460
00:30:24,080 --> 00:30:25,308
Hastily yours, Edgar Hopper.

461
00:30:25,480 --> 00:30:28,199
That is my final word on the subject.
Hastily yours, Edgar Hopper.

462
00:30:28,360 --> 00:30:30,669
I've got to have 10,000 bed springs
at once.

463
00:30:30,840 --> 00:30:34,071
Hostily yours, Edgar Haper...
Heaper. Hop...

464
00:30:34,240 --> 00:30:35,514
Hastily yours, the hophead.

465
00:30:35,680 --> 00:30:38,353
Hastily yours, the boss.

466
00:30:38,560 --> 00:30:41,757
- I'd like that all in triplicate.
- No one can work like this.

467
00:30:41,920 --> 00:30:44,070
The pace is too fast.
We're not machines.

468
00:30:44,240 --> 00:30:47,073
- We're human beings.
- Miss Bickford, there's no place here...

469
00:30:47,240 --> 00:30:51,438
...for anyone who cannot keep up with
the pace of modern living. You are fired.

470
00:31:40,640 --> 00:31:42,198
[PHONE RINGS]

471
00:31:45,080 --> 00:31:46,559
Yes?

472
00:31:46,720 --> 00:31:47,709
It happened.

473
00:31:47,880 --> 00:31:49,029
[LAUGHING]

474
00:31:49,200 --> 00:31:50,633
Get me my house. Quick.

475
00:31:50,800 --> 00:31:52,870
You just closed the deal?
My wife. Hurry.

476
00:31:53,040 --> 00:31:54,712
Leonard Crawley
handed over the keys.

477
00:31:54,880 --> 00:31:57,235
Louisa. Louisa. Louisa.

478
00:31:57,640 --> 00:31:59,153
[PHONE RINGS]

479
00:31:59,920 --> 00:32:02,229
- Hello.
- EDGAR: <i>Louisa, it happened</i>.

480
00:32:02,400 --> 00:32:04,834
- What happened?
- The next time you walk down Main...

481
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:07,275
...there won't be Crawley's.
It'll say Hopper's.

482
00:32:07,440 --> 00:32:11,479
Louisa, I did it. I wiped him out.
He's through in this town.

483
00:32:11,920 --> 00:32:14,115
Well, I guess that's what
you wanted, isn't it?

484
00:32:14,280 --> 00:32:18,432
EDGAR: <i>I got what I wanted. And I got</i>
<i>money, wealth, success, position</i>.

485
00:32:18,600 --> 00:32:22,070
And next year, this town
is gonna be called Hopperville.

486
00:32:22,240 --> 00:32:27,075
And how did I get all these things?
Through work. Just good, hard work.

487
00:32:28,040 --> 00:32:32,318
Which all goes to prove that
a little hard work never killed anybody.

488
00:32:37,520 --> 00:32:39,556
LAWYER:
"And outside of the bequest...

489
00:32:39,720 --> 00:32:43,395
...of one roll of chicken wire
to Leonard Crawley...

490
00:32:43,560 --> 00:32:46,632
...I bequeath my entire fortune
and worldly goods...

491
00:32:46,800 --> 00:32:50,998
...to my wife,
Louisa May Foster Hopper".

492
00:32:51,160 --> 00:32:54,072
LOUISA: <i>Edgar had left me</i>
<i>approximately $ 2 million</i>...

493
00:32:54,240 --> 00:32:55,878
...<i>in cash and securities</i>.

494
00:32:56,040 --> 00:33:00,636
<i>And as Thoreau probably never said,</i>
<i>that's a lot of lettuce</i>.

495
00:33:02,320 --> 00:33:05,471
But, my dear,
you mustn't think that this...

496
00:33:05,640 --> 00:33:07,392
...in any way makes you a witch.

497
00:33:07,560 --> 00:33:10,996
Of course,
it is tragic that Edgar died...

498
00:33:11,160 --> 00:33:13,151
...but one swallow
doesn't make a summer.

499
00:33:13,320 --> 00:33:17,438
Your behavior sounds exemplary
to say the least, the very least.

500
00:33:17,680 --> 00:33:21,593
Why did Edgar change that way?

501
00:33:22,040 --> 00:33:23,393
Normal.

502
00:33:23,560 --> 00:33:27,269
Quite normal. You see, he was
the weakest of the tribe...

503
00:33:27,440 --> 00:33:29,635
...who had somehow
won the prize, you...

504
00:33:29,800 --> 00:33:31,916
...without really having
had to fight for you.

505
00:33:32,080 --> 00:33:34,150
Latent feelings
of inadequacy lay dormant...

506
00:33:34,320 --> 00:33:37,039
...until he was triggered
by Leonard parading before you...

507
00:33:37,200 --> 00:33:38,952
...in his rich, many colored feathers.

508
00:33:39,120 --> 00:33:43,079
Edgar, naturally, felt impelled
to get even more feathers.

509
00:33:43,240 --> 00:33:48,234
And driven by this ego drive,
he smothered in his own feathers.

510
00:33:48,440 --> 00:33:50,271
It happens every day, you know.

511
00:33:50,440 --> 00:33:54,752
Tell me, what happened
to the other feather... Fellow.

512
00:33:54,920 --> 00:33:57,150
This Leonard?

513
00:33:57,320 --> 00:33:59,959
I never heard from him again.

514
00:34:01,720 --> 00:34:03,597
Oh.

515
00:34:04,360 --> 00:34:06,191
Dr. Steffanson...

516
00:34:06,360 --> 00:34:08,032
[SCREAMING]

517
00:34:08,800 --> 00:34:10,916
Louisa. I'm sorry. Just relax.

518
00:34:11,080 --> 00:34:12,354
Oh, I'm terribly sorry.

519
00:34:14,400 --> 00:34:15,674
There.

520
00:34:15,840 --> 00:34:17,239
Now, please, please.

521
00:34:17,400 --> 00:34:19,152
- Just relax.
- Yes.

522
00:34:19,320 --> 00:34:20,833
Try to relax.

523
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:24,037
You were saying about Leonard.
Leonard.

524
00:34:24,200 --> 00:34:26,350
Where did Leonard go?

525
00:34:26,520 --> 00:34:29,796
Uh, well...

526
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:32,798
...he just walked away
like a plucked chicken.

527
00:34:32,960 --> 00:34:36,794
- Normal. Quite, quite normal.
- Yes.

528
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:38,479
Well, I...

529
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:41,719
I put all the money in the bank...

530
00:34:41,880 --> 00:34:44,155
- ...and I gave the house to Mama.
- Uh-huh.

531
00:34:44,320 --> 00:34:46,914
And I took a small allowance
for myself...

532
00:34:47,080 --> 00:34:49,310
- ...and I got out of Crawleyville.
- Mm-hm.

533
00:34:50,320 --> 00:34:54,552
I took a trip to Europe. Alone.
To Paris.

534
00:34:54,800 --> 00:35:00,670
I wanted to forget, and I was
determined never to marry again.

535
00:35:18,160 --> 00:35:20,674
LOUISA: <i>The bus tours were thrilling</i>
<i>and exhausting</i>.

536
00:35:21,200 --> 00:35:22,872
[YELLING IN FRENCH]

537
00:35:24,280 --> 00:35:26,271
[HORNS HONKING]

538
00:35:34,480 --> 00:35:36,869
[SPEAKS FRENCH POORLY]

539
00:35:41,600 --> 00:35:44,398
LARRY: I ain't got all day, lady.
Where do you wanna go?

540
00:35:44,560 --> 00:35:47,074
- Oh, you speak English.
- LARRY: All of us foreigners do.

541
00:35:47,240 --> 00:35:48,878
It's compulsory.

542
00:35:49,080 --> 00:35:50,957
You American?

543
00:35:51,520 --> 00:35:54,956
No, lady, I'm a Russian spy
for the CIA.

544
00:35:55,120 --> 00:35:57,634
Well, what'll it be?
Go to the American ghetto...

545
00:35:57,800 --> 00:36:01,349
...or the bar of the George V,
or go visit some of your phony friends...

546
00:36:01,520 --> 00:36:04,034
...learning about life
at Les Deux Magots.

547
00:36:05,360 --> 00:36:07,999
Well, frankly,
I'd like to do either...

548
00:36:08,160 --> 00:36:09,912
...but I don't know anybody here.

549
00:36:10,080 --> 00:36:12,548
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

550
00:36:24,280 --> 00:36:25,952
[HORNS HONKING]

551
00:36:33,240 --> 00:36:34,673
Well?

552
00:36:35,280 --> 00:36:36,713
Well...

553
00:36:38,400 --> 00:36:40,391
I think I'd like to see
some more pictures.

554
00:36:40,560 --> 00:36:42,710
I've been to the Louvre.
That was wonderful.

555
00:36:42,920 --> 00:36:46,310
The Louvre. Now, what is that?
It's a garbage pail of the arts.

556
00:36:46,480 --> 00:36:48,277
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

557
00:36:50,120 --> 00:36:51,473
Well...

558
00:36:51,640 --> 00:36:53,835
How about the show
at the Galeries Lafayette?

559
00:36:54,000 --> 00:36:56,389
That's a department store.
But I'd rather hang up...

560
00:36:56,560 --> 00:36:59,199
...one of their face towels
than some of that other junk.

561
00:36:59,360 --> 00:37:01,476
I'm sure you're an expert taxi driver...

562
00:37:01,640 --> 00:37:03,471
...and I don't mean
to belittle your profession...

563
00:37:03,640 --> 00:37:06,393
...but why should I listen
to your opinion on art?

564
00:37:06,920 --> 00:37:09,832
Because I happen to be
one of five people today...

565
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:12,514
...who could definitely
be called an artist.

566
00:37:12,680 --> 00:37:14,432
Maybe six including Frieda.

567
00:37:15,200 --> 00:37:18,795
- Who's Frieda?
- A chimpanzee on my block.

568
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:20,752
[CHIMP CHATTERING]

569
00:37:21,280 --> 00:37:23,589
Oh, that's great. That's great.

570
00:37:23,760 --> 00:37:27,435
I mean, you see a technique like that,
it wipes you out. I go ape.

571
00:37:27,600 --> 00:37:30,592
- What is it?
- What is it? Innocence.

572
00:37:30,760 --> 00:37:32,079
Van Gogh had it.

573
00:37:32,240 --> 00:37:35,550
But he had to chop his ear off
in order to free himself.

574
00:37:35,720 --> 00:37:39,349
- Free himself from what?
- Intellectual hang-up.

575
00:37:39,520 --> 00:37:43,593
If we could all do that. Go back to
a life like that. Uncluttered, unhung.

576
00:37:44,840 --> 00:37:47,354
- Simple.
- Oh.

577
00:37:47,520 --> 00:37:49,590
LARRY: Frieda had the best teacher
in the world.

578
00:37:49,760 --> 00:37:51,637
Rene Carrere, there.

579
00:37:51,960 --> 00:37:55,475
I'm very happy to meet you, Mr. Carrere.
I'm Louisa May Hopper.

580
00:37:56,120 --> 00:37:59,032
You don't look anything
like the Emile Desjardins...

581
00:37:59,200 --> 00:38:03,113
- ...it said you were in your cab.
- The name is Larry Flint.

582
00:38:03,360 --> 00:38:05,351
I take Emile's cab out for him
once a year.

583
00:38:05,520 --> 00:38:07,590
The day his wife has a baby.

584
00:38:07,760 --> 00:38:09,751
Frieda is finished now.

585
00:38:09,920 --> 00:38:12,115
It's a masterpiece.

586
00:38:12,280 --> 00:38:15,078
Boy! Look at the line...

587
00:38:15,240 --> 00:38:18,152
...and the color and the sweep
and the texture.

588
00:38:18,840 --> 00:38:20,831
Marvelous.

589
00:38:21,560 --> 00:38:27,078
A testament to the human spirit.
Total primitive articulation.

590
00:38:27,480 --> 00:38:30,278
- Does Frieda's work sell?
- Sell?!

591
00:38:30,440 --> 00:38:32,590
You think Frieda cares
whether her work sells?

592
00:38:32,760 --> 00:38:34,352
You think I care if my work sells?

593
00:38:34,520 --> 00:38:36,636
Typical American yardstick,
the eternal buck.

594
00:38:36,800 --> 00:38:40,110
- That's why I left the place.
- Well, Mr. Flint, I was only asking.

595
00:38:40,280 --> 00:38:41,269
And banan...

596
00:38:41,440 --> 00:38:42,429
[GUNSHOT]
[SCREAMS]

597
00:38:42,600 --> 00:38:43,635
What's that?

598
00:38:44,080 --> 00:38:45,911
LARRY:
She's at it again.

599
00:38:46,080 --> 00:38:47,877
LOUISA:
Is someone being murdered?

600
00:38:48,040 --> 00:38:49,837
Are we going to the police?

601
00:38:50,120 --> 00:38:52,156
[GUNSHOTS]

602
00:38:52,320 --> 00:38:54,675
Hey, Larry.
She's shot three already.

603
00:39:00,280 --> 00:39:01,872
Hey, Polly. You're working again.

604
00:39:02,040 --> 00:39:04,156
For weeks I thought
I couldn't paint again...

605
00:39:04,320 --> 00:39:06,959
...and now suddenly it's all come back.

606
00:39:12,720 --> 00:39:14,472
One of the greats.

607
00:39:14,640 --> 00:39:17,950
- That picture makes me sick.
- Thank you. Thank you very much.

608
00:39:18,120 --> 00:39:20,190
Good. Feel sick.
It should make you feel sick.

609
00:39:20,360 --> 00:39:23,272
It's destruction, pure and simple.
That's what today is about.

610
00:39:23,480 --> 00:39:25,948
That technique is her way
of expressing it.

611
00:39:29,080 --> 00:39:32,868
LOUISA: <i>What was I doing in Paris,</i>
<i>4500 miles away from home?</i>

612
00:39:33,040 --> 00:39:35,838
<i>It was fate</i>.
<i>I had come to meet Larry Flint</i>...

613
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:37,911
...<i>an unspoiled, dedicated artist</i>.

614
00:39:38,120 --> 00:39:41,476
<i>Searching, in his own troubled way,</i>
<i>for the simple life</i>.

615
00:39:41,640 --> 00:39:44,029
<i>Suddenly I knew</i>
<i>I wanted to share that life</i>.

616
00:39:45,880 --> 00:39:48,917
<i>Well, I never did</i>
<i>go back to the Ritz</i>.

617
00:39:49,080 --> 00:39:50,479
<i>I'll never forget the wedding</i>.

618
00:39:50,800 --> 00:39:52,916
<i>Frieda made a lovely bridesmaid</i>.

619
00:39:53,080 --> 00:39:56,993
<i>As a matter of fact, she caught</i>
<i>the bridal bouquet and ate it</i>.

620
00:39:58,560 --> 00:40:01,552
<i>For a while, Larry and I</i>
<i>led an idyllic life</i>.

621
00:40:01,720 --> 00:40:04,234
<i>As I look back on it,</i>
<i>it all seems like one of those</i>...

622
00:40:04,400 --> 00:40:06,868
...<i>wickedly romantic French movies</i>.

623
00:40:10,960 --> 00:40:11,949
[SINGING "FRERE JACQUES"]

624
00:40:24,520 --> 00:40:25,919
LARRY:
Louisa!

625
00:40:35,520 --> 00:40:36,794
To your health, Louisa!

626
00:40:41,080 --> 00:40:43,469
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

627
00:42:19,200 --> 00:42:21,589
LOUISA: <i>The rest of the time,</i>
<i>I kept the house</i>.

628
00:42:21,920 --> 00:42:24,388
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

629
00:42:40,080 --> 00:42:42,116
This week's dinner.

630
00:42:42,400 --> 00:42:45,517
Darling, beautiful.

631
00:42:45,960 --> 00:42:48,633
- How did you...?
- <i>Opus 752</i>.

632
00:42:48,800 --> 00:42:52,236
But, darling, that's one
of your most beautiful paintings.

633
00:42:52,400 --> 00:42:54,470
Well, we can see it
at the butcher shop.

634
00:42:54,640 --> 00:42:57,313
Blanchard has it hanging
over the tripe and sweetbreads.

635
00:42:57,480 --> 00:42:59,630
I've told you many times
in the United States...

636
00:42:59,840 --> 00:43:01,239
Won't touch it.

637
00:43:01,400 --> 00:43:05,109
Not a nickel. Money corrupts.
Art erupts.

638
00:43:05,400 --> 00:43:09,154
- That's a beautiful saying.
- It's immortal. I just made it up.

639
00:43:09,320 --> 00:43:12,676
Hey, say, listen. Why don't you bring
some of that downstairs for me?

640
00:43:12,840 --> 00:43:15,673
I've got some erupting to do.

641
00:43:19,520 --> 00:43:21,670
[CLATTERING]

642
00:43:26,400 --> 00:43:29,198
[MACHINE SIREN WAILING]

643
00:43:32,680 --> 00:43:34,238
[HONKING]

644
00:43:36,800 --> 00:43:37,789
[CLANGS]

645
00:43:40,520 --> 00:43:42,192
[RINGING]

646
00:43:45,120 --> 00:43:48,908
Darling, your soup's on. Soup.

647
00:43:55,400 --> 00:43:58,756
Darling, must you make
so much noise when you paint?

648
00:43:58,920 --> 00:44:00,558
Ain't no other way, honey.

649
00:44:00,720 --> 00:44:02,950
Tools of my trade,
like I told you, see.

650
00:44:03,120 --> 00:44:05,634
The sound, the sonic vibrations,
they go in there.

651
00:44:05,800 --> 00:44:08,268
That gets transmitted
to that photoelectric cell...

652
00:44:08,440 --> 00:44:11,591
...which gives those dynamic impulses
to the brushes and the arms.

653
00:44:11,760 --> 00:44:16,788
And it's a fusion of the mechanized
world and a human soul.

654
00:44:16,960 --> 00:44:19,918
That's the only affirmative statement
being made in art today.

655
00:44:20,200 --> 00:44:22,509
I'm sorry, I forgot.

656
00:44:22,840 --> 00:44:24,671
It's a terrible thing being so dumb.

657
00:44:24,840 --> 00:44:27,718
You're really not so dumb, honey,
because to tell the truth...

658
00:44:27,880 --> 00:44:29,359
...I don't understand it myself.

659
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:46,911
[GROANS]

660
00:44:47,120 --> 00:44:49,475
I left the machine on.

661
00:44:50,040 --> 00:44:51,792
LOUISA:
Larry.

662
00:44:51,960 --> 00:44:53,678
Larry.

663
00:44:54,360 --> 00:44:56,954
I know this probably sounds stupid
to you...

664
00:44:57,120 --> 00:44:58,439
...but...

665
00:44:58,600 --> 00:45:00,989
...what if we take a record
and we put it on...

666
00:45:01,160 --> 00:45:03,720
- ...and we play it through the...
- The sonic palette.

667
00:45:03,920 --> 00:45:05,194
The sonic palette.

668
00:45:05,360 --> 00:45:07,316
LARRY:
Silly kid. Go ahead.

669
00:45:08,040 --> 00:45:11,635
Mendelssohn's "Spring Song".
It's my favorite.

670
00:45:15,800 --> 00:45:18,439
[MENDELSSOHN'S
"SPRING SONG" PLAYS]

671
00:46:15,160 --> 00:46:17,151
Larry.

672
00:46:17,400 --> 00:46:19,072
Larry.

673
00:46:19,560 --> 00:46:22,028
I like the ones you make
with your own noises.

674
00:46:22,200 --> 00:46:24,156
They're the real you.

675
00:46:26,200 --> 00:46:28,077
Yeah, but...

676
00:46:28,240 --> 00:46:31,994
...I hate to waste a good canvas.
So I might try to pay a bill with it.

677
00:46:33,600 --> 00:46:35,670
Maybe the butcher
won't know the difference...

678
00:46:35,840 --> 00:46:38,274
...between a real Larry Flint
and a Mendelssohn.

679
00:46:42,200 --> 00:46:45,351
Hey, Louisa. Hey. Guess what.

680
00:46:45,520 --> 00:46:48,193
- What, darling?
- I didn't leave it at the butcher's.

681
00:46:48,360 --> 00:46:51,796
I was showing it to him, and there's
this customer buying pig's knuckles...

682
00:46:51,960 --> 00:46:55,396
...so he looks at the picture,
and then he puts on his glasses...

683
00:46:55,560 --> 00:46:58,677
...and he gives me his card,
and he gives me 40,000 francs.

684
00:46:58,840 --> 00:47:01,195
That's almost $200.

685
00:47:01,840 --> 00:47:05,992
Why, that's wonderful, darling.
All from that silly little idea.

686
00:47:06,160 --> 00:47:09,038
Yeah, well, I gotta go downstairs
and get to work.

687
00:47:10,560 --> 00:47:14,553
I'll be listening
for all those dear, funny, little noises.

688
00:47:17,120 --> 00:47:19,554
[CLATTERING]

689
00:47:29,600 --> 00:47:32,512
[CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING]

690
00:47:55,480 --> 00:47:57,471
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

691
00:48:29,160 --> 00:48:30,957
LOUISA:
<i>The show was a smashing success</i>.

692
00:48:32,080 --> 00:48:34,719
<i>Larry was famous</i>
<i>and rich overnight</i>.

693
00:48:34,880 --> 00:48:37,952
<i>In the middle of this excitement,</i>
<i>I was filled with apprehension</i>...

694
00:48:38,120 --> 00:48:39,712
...<i>although I tried to conceal it</i>.

695
00:48:39,880 --> 00:48:42,394
- Congratulations, master.
- I am insufferably honored.

696
00:48:42,560 --> 00:48:43,675
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

697
00:48:43,840 --> 00:48:47,150
- Frieda and I are very happy.
- At last, painting which is music...

698
00:48:47,320 --> 00:48:49,550
...and music which is painting.
How do you do it?

699
00:48:49,720 --> 00:48:52,439
Oh, how can anyone explain
the workings of the inner man?

700
00:48:52,600 --> 00:48:56,639
Actually, the act of creation might best
be described as pure animal instinct.

701
00:48:56,800 --> 00:49:00,475
If only Beethoven were alive
to just hear this painting.

702
00:49:00,640 --> 00:49:02,949
Yes. Poor Ludwig.
I think he'd be very pleased.

703
00:49:03,120 --> 00:49:06,476
Your paintings make me
want to kneel, pray and cry.

704
00:49:06,640 --> 00:49:08,790
In that case, baroness,
why don't you buy one?

705
00:49:08,960 --> 00:49:11,394
Then you can kneel and pray
and cry at home.

706
00:49:11,560 --> 00:49:13,312
- Sensation, master.
- Please.

707
00:49:13,480 --> 00:49:16,916
Please. Please,
let me introduce you to all Paris.

708
00:49:17,080 --> 00:49:20,311
Thank you. But me wife and I
don't think much of the high places.

709
00:49:20,480 --> 00:49:23,631
We'll go back to our little garage
and attic. I got work to do.

710
00:49:23,800 --> 00:49:24,789
[LAUGHING]

711
00:49:24,960 --> 00:49:25,949
[BURPS]

712
00:49:26,360 --> 00:49:28,828
LOUISA: <i>But, of course,</i>
<i>we didn't go back to the old place</i>.

713
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:30,956
<i>We had a lovely house</i>
<i>on Ile St. Louis</i>.

714
00:49:31,160 --> 00:49:32,673
<i>But Larry was never there</i>.

715
00:49:32,840 --> 00:49:34,831
<i>If he wasn't entertaining</i>
<i>at the gallery</i>...

716
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:37,230
...<i>he was at his studio</i>
<i>just outside of Paris</i>.

717
00:49:37,400 --> 00:49:40,312
[CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING]

718
00:49:40,960 --> 00:49:42,359
[EXPLODING]

719
00:49:52,320 --> 00:49:54,356
LOUISA:
<i>I was tired of being alone</i>.

720
00:49:54,520 --> 00:49:56,590
<i>Tired of wearing</i>
<i>these ridiculous outfits</i>...

721
00:49:56,760 --> 00:49:59,957
...<i>Larry painted for me</i>.
<i>What kind of life was this?</i>

722
00:50:00,120 --> 00:50:04,432
<i>I was just another canvas to him</i>.
<i>Just another walking catalog</i>.

723
00:50:04,600 --> 00:50:07,160
<i>Where was the simple life</i>
<i>Larry and I had had?</i>

724
00:50:07,320 --> 00:50:09,038
<i>That</i> vie de Bohčme.

725
00:50:09,200 --> 00:50:12,272
<i>He was obsessed with success</i>.
<i>I had to get him back</i>.

726
00:50:12,440 --> 00:50:14,795
<i>I couldn't let that happen to me</i>
<i>a second time</i>.

727
00:50:14,960 --> 00:50:16,757
<i>Suddenly, I had an idea</i>.

728
00:50:16,960 --> 00:50:19,997
[CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING]

729
00:50:37,520 --> 00:50:41,354
What are you doing up there?
Get down. Down.

730
00:50:41,960 --> 00:50:43,678
What the...?

731
00:50:45,680 --> 00:50:48,752
Stop that. Right now.
Stop that. Stop that.

732
00:50:49,920 --> 00:50:51,194
Come on, now. Stop that.

733
00:50:54,880 --> 00:50:57,678
- Louisa, what are you doing here?
- Darling...

734
00:50:57,840 --> 00:50:59,398
...I haven't seen you in so long.

735
00:50:59,560 --> 00:51:02,393
We had dinner together only last week.
What do you want?

736
00:51:02,640 --> 00:51:04,710
I have a surprise for you.

737
00:51:05,320 --> 00:51:06,912
LARRY: A-ha.

738
00:51:12,960 --> 00:51:14,712
Larry.

739
00:51:15,400 --> 00:51:17,197
Larry.

740
00:51:17,400 --> 00:51:19,436
Larry!

741
00:51:20,280 --> 00:51:22,032
Look who's here.

742
00:51:22,200 --> 00:51:25,397
- Well, how's Frieda?
- Painting better than ever.

743
00:51:25,560 --> 00:51:28,597
Larry. Larry, we have missed you, Larry.

744
00:51:28,760 --> 00:51:30,955
Oh, yes. I've missed you too.

745
00:51:35,920 --> 00:51:38,070
LOUISA:
Larry, we have a picnic.

746
00:51:38,240 --> 00:51:40,674
Some bread and wine and cheese.

747
00:51:40,840 --> 00:51:43,115
- And I thought we could all go.
- No. I'm sorry.

748
00:51:43,280 --> 00:51:45,999
I'm working against a deadline.
This is for Neiman Marcus.

749
00:51:46,160 --> 00:51:47,832
That's a department store in Texas.

750
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:50,560
One hundred and fifty thou.

751
00:51:50,720 --> 00:51:53,712
I've gotta get it rolled up
and on a jet by tomorrow.

752
00:51:54,200 --> 00:51:56,031
[SINGS INDISTINCTLY]

753
00:51:56,600 --> 00:51:58,591
What are you doing up there?

754
00:51:58,760 --> 00:51:59,749
[GROANS]

755
00:51:59,920 --> 00:52:03,117
I never should have had these
damn things made in Paris.

756
00:52:04,800 --> 00:52:06,597
What are you doing?
Where are you going?

757
00:52:06,760 --> 00:52:08,910
Get back in line there.
Stop that.

758
00:52:09,080 --> 00:52:12,436
- Stop that. Get back in line!
- I'm terribly sorry, Rene.

759
00:52:12,920 --> 00:52:14,751
LARRY:
Get back there. Get back there!

760
00:52:15,520 --> 00:52:17,750
Larry, what is the matter with you?

761
00:52:17,920 --> 00:52:19,797
- What is the matter?
- LARRY: Get back there.

762
00:52:20,000 --> 00:52:23,072
RENE: Larry, why can't it be
the way it used to be?

763
00:52:23,440 --> 00:52:25,476
Larry, I never dreamed
this could happen.

764
00:52:25,640 --> 00:52:28,473
What is the matter with you, Larry?

765
00:52:29,040 --> 00:52:31,713
What is the matter with you?
What is the matter?

766
00:52:32,360 --> 00:52:34,237
[CLASSICAL MUSIC SPEEDING]

767
00:52:34,880 --> 00:52:37,314
LOUISA:
Come on, Rene, let's go.

768
00:52:54,200 --> 00:52:56,270
[CLASSICAL MUSIC SLOWING]

769
00:53:11,400 --> 00:53:15,393
One hundred and fifty thou!

770
00:53:16,520 --> 00:53:18,033
What the...?

771
00:53:18,560 --> 00:53:20,391
[GROANS]

772
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:30,797
[EXPLODING]

773
00:53:34,760 --> 00:53:36,830
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

774
00:53:42,360 --> 00:53:43,793
Pardon, madame.

775
00:53:43,960 --> 00:53:46,155
"I, Larry Flint, bequeath all my"...

776
00:53:46,320 --> 00:53:48,436
LOUISA: <i>What Larry Flint</i>
<i>had left me in cash</i>...

777
00:53:48,600 --> 00:53:50,636
...<i>plus the sale</i>
<i>of his remaining pictures</i>...

778
00:53:50,800 --> 00:53:54,315
...<i>brought me in the neighborhood</i>
<i>of $4 million in American money</i>.

779
00:53:54,480 --> 00:53:57,597
<i>It was an amount even Picasso</i>
<i>wouldn't be ashamed of</i>.

780
00:53:58,480 --> 00:54:01,438
<i>After several months</i>
<i>of trying to lose myself in Paris</i>...

781
00:54:01,600 --> 00:54:03,795
...<i>I decided to leave</i>.

782
00:54:15,800 --> 00:54:17,358
I was here an hour early.

783
00:54:17,520 --> 00:54:19,954
You kept me sitting in that lounge,
and everyone said:

784
00:54:20,120 --> 00:54:22,315
"Don't worry, you'll hear
the announcement".

785
00:54:22,480 --> 00:54:24,198
We phoned for them
to hold up for you.

786
00:54:24,360 --> 00:54:26,157
But I guess they didn't get
the message.

787
00:54:26,360 --> 00:54:30,273
- Believe me, believe me, it's just...
- All my luggage is on that plane.

788
00:54:30,440 --> 00:54:33,910
Oh, I had my heart set
on getting out of here tonight.

789
00:54:34,080 --> 00:54:35,479
[HORN HONKING]

790
00:54:36,360 --> 00:54:38,032
[LAUGHING]

791
00:54:45,760 --> 00:54:48,558
But I can't possibly stay in Paris
for another day.

792
00:54:48,760 --> 00:54:50,671
You miss the last trolley
back to town?

793
00:54:50,840 --> 00:54:53,718
Mr. Anderson, should I have
the plane brought back?

794
00:54:53,920 --> 00:54:56,559
- No, no, I'll take it from here.
- Thank you, Mr. Anderson.

795
00:54:56,720 --> 00:54:59,757
Excuse me, Mr. Anderson.
Overseas call, sir. San Francisco.

796
00:54:59,920 --> 00:55:02,992
Excuse me. Hello? Uh-huh.

797
00:55:03,200 --> 00:55:04,952
LOUISA:
<i>I recognized him immediately</i>.

798
00:55:05,160 --> 00:55:09,472
<i>Unbalding, glamorous Rod Anderson Jr,</i>
<i>millionaire tycoon</i>.

799
00:55:09,640 --> 00:55:12,108
<i>Up from riches,</i>
<i>inheriting 10 million</i>...

800
00:55:12,280 --> 00:55:14,510
...<i>from Senior Anderson's</i>
<i>maple-syrup empire</i>.

801
00:55:14,680 --> 00:55:17,797
<i>Unmarried, he seemed to have no</i>
<i>trouble in getting what he wanted</i>...

802
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:21,276
- ...<i>in business or in pleasure</i>.
- Buy it. Thank you.

803
00:55:21,440 --> 00:55:23,510
Well, Mrs. Flint,
where would you like to go?

804
00:55:23,680 --> 00:55:27,036
Sorry about your loss. I saw you at one
of your late husband's openings.

805
00:55:27,200 --> 00:55:29,839
I didn't buy anything, though.
I don't like his paintings.

806
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:32,719
Well, I don't like your airplanes.
Where are you going?

807
00:55:32,880 --> 00:55:35,713
New York, Miami, Irkutsk,
anyplace you'd like to go.

808
00:55:35,880 --> 00:55:37,871
I flew in from New York
for some party.

809
00:55:38,040 --> 00:55:41,112
I stayed about a half an hour
and I'd had it. I don't like parties.

810
00:55:41,280 --> 00:55:43,840
So you just put on your Superman suit
and fly away home.

811
00:55:44,000 --> 00:55:45,718
That's right. And there it is.

812
00:55:46,400 --> 00:55:48,868
Or don't you accept hitches
from strange men?

813
00:55:49,040 --> 00:55:50,678
Oh, I know who you are,
Mr. Anderson.

814
00:55:50,840 --> 00:55:52,831
I don't know
if I'll be very good company.

815
00:55:53,000 --> 00:55:55,230
I just don't...
I don't have much small talk.

816
00:55:55,400 --> 00:55:57,038
I haven't any time for small talk.

817
00:55:57,200 --> 00:56:00,033
Excuse me, Mr. Anderson.
Overseas call, Hong Kong calling.

818
00:56:00,200 --> 00:56:01,428
Excuse me.

819
00:56:01,600 --> 00:56:05,912
Yeah. All right. Sell it. Thank you.

820
00:56:06,120 --> 00:56:08,554
Well, where shall it be?

821
00:56:08,720 --> 00:56:11,075
- New York.
- New York it is.

822
00:56:17,560 --> 00:56:21,348
LOUISA: <i>What was I getting into?</i>
<i>What was on that plane?</i>

823
00:56:21,520 --> 00:56:22,794
<i>I looked at the name of it:</i>

824
00:56:23,440 --> 00:56:24,634
Melissa.

825
00:56:24,840 --> 00:56:27,115
<i>Naturally, it would</i>
<i>be named after a woman</i>.

826
00:56:27,280 --> 00:56:30,238
<i>I'd heard enough about</i>
<i>those dissolute playboys</i>.

827
00:56:30,800 --> 00:56:32,791
[LAUGHING AND CHATTERING]

828
00:56:46,360 --> 00:56:48,715
What are you doing after the orgy?

829
00:56:52,200 --> 00:56:55,033
ROD:
The plane is ready.

830
00:56:55,600 --> 00:56:59,149
- Pretty name, <i>Melissa</i>.
- Someone I knew a long time ago.

831
00:57:17,640 --> 00:57:20,234
- Good evening, Mr. Anderson.
- Good evening, Mark.

832
00:57:20,440 --> 00:57:21,759
Mark, this is Mrs. Flint.

833
00:57:21,920 --> 00:57:23,911
- She'll be flying back with us.
- Mrs. Flint.

834
00:57:24,080 --> 00:57:25,672
- How is the weather?
- It's clear...

835
00:57:25,840 --> 00:57:28,115
- ...all the way through to New York.
- Excellent.

836
00:57:33,560 --> 00:57:36,950
- ROD: Good evening, Willard.
- Good evening, Mr. Anderson.

837
00:57:37,640 --> 00:57:39,995
- Willard, this is Mrs. Flint.
- How do you do?

838
00:57:40,160 --> 00:57:42,469
- Mrs. Flint will be flying back with us.
- Yes, sir.

839
00:57:42,680 --> 00:57:44,398
Her bags left on the 11: 19.

840
00:57:44,560 --> 00:57:47,916
You have them picked up
at Idlewild and delivered to...?

841
00:57:48,480 --> 00:57:50,675
- The Montclair Hotel?
- Is that your favorite?

842
00:57:50,880 --> 00:57:55,237
Well, I've never been in New York.
Only for a few hours en route.

843
00:57:55,400 --> 00:57:58,119
You'd better make that
my suite at the St. Regis, Willard.

844
00:57:58,280 --> 00:58:01,829
- Very good, sir.
- It's reserved for visiting executives.

845
00:58:02,040 --> 00:58:05,157
I camp about 10 blocks further up
the street on Fifth Avenue.

846
00:58:05,320 --> 00:58:08,312
Willard, have the chef come around
and take Mrs. Flint's order.

847
00:58:08,480 --> 00:58:10,436
- Yes, sir.
- You can have anything you like.

848
00:58:10,600 --> 00:58:12,113
We have some fine wines aboard.

849
00:58:12,280 --> 00:58:15,113
- I'll just have my usual.
- Yes, sir.

850
00:58:15,320 --> 00:58:17,072
Whatever you have
is all right with me.

851
00:58:17,240 --> 00:58:18,514
Oh, really?

852
00:58:18,680 --> 00:58:23,629
My usual is two soft-boiled eggs,
gluten toast and a glass of yogurt.

853
00:58:23,880 --> 00:58:27,953
And, Willard, Mrs. Flint will have
the crčme Senegalese, Steak Diane...

854
00:58:28,120 --> 00:58:30,156
...pommes soufflé, profiteroles...

855
00:58:30,320 --> 00:58:33,437
...with chocolate sauce and
break out a bottle of La Tache.

856
00:58:33,600 --> 00:58:35,989
- WILLARD: Very good, sir.
- That'll be all, Willard, thank you.

857
00:58:36,200 --> 00:58:40,830
Now, let's step into the bar. I'll make
you one of my very special martinis.

858
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:45,551
Thank you, no.
I'll have a Scotch on the "rotch".

859
00:58:45,800 --> 00:58:49,110
- On the rocks.
- Oh, very well.

860
00:58:49,960 --> 00:58:52,679
I was raised on maple syrup,
you know.

861
00:58:53,200 --> 00:58:55,031
Cured me of drinking anything at all.

862
00:58:55,200 --> 00:58:58,272
- Well, then I won't have...
- No, you go right ahead. Drink up.

863
00:58:58,480 --> 00:59:00,038
It's good for you.

864
00:59:01,720 --> 00:59:04,632
The telephone. Watkins, in Chicago.

865
00:59:04,840 --> 00:59:06,432
Excuse me.

866
00:59:16,280 --> 00:59:18,794
You know, you really are
rather beautiful.

867
00:59:20,920 --> 00:59:22,672
But is that your hair?

868
00:59:22,840 --> 00:59:24,353
Yeah, hello.

869
00:59:24,920 --> 00:59:26,558
Okay, you just sit tight.

870
00:59:26,760 --> 00:59:28,671
No, no. I think
Prescott's bluffing anyway.

871
00:59:28,840 --> 00:59:30,637
LOUISA:
<i>True, there was no orgy onboard</i>.

872
00:59:30,800 --> 00:59:33,519
<i>He wasn't the Diamond Jim Brady</i>
<i>of the jet set</i>.

873
00:59:33,680 --> 00:59:37,389
<i>But he was arrogant, cold, sure</i>
<i>of himself, ordering people around</i>.

874
00:59:37,640 --> 00:59:41,758
<i>Another object lesson in what money</i>
<i>and power can do to a human being</i>.

875
00:59:41,920 --> 00:59:45,674
<i>But for all of it, he really seemed</i>
<i>to be a miserable and lonely man</i>.

876
00:59:45,880 --> 00:59:47,518
<i>Why, he never even smiled</i>.

877
00:59:47,680 --> 00:59:51,389
<i>Not once had a smile</i>
<i>lit that stony, sunless face</i>.

878
00:59:51,560 --> 00:59:54,438
Well, a tycoon's work
is never finished, is it?

879
00:59:54,600 --> 00:59:58,036
- That's what you call yourself, isn't it?
- Absolutely. Absolutely.

880
00:59:58,240 --> 01:00:02,279
Every morning I get up and say
to myself, "Good morning, tycoon".

881
01:00:02,600 --> 01:00:05,034
I know you don't approve of me,
Mrs. Flint...

882
01:00:05,200 --> 01:00:08,033
...but that need be of no concern
to either one of us.

883
01:00:08,200 --> 01:00:10,270
I'm going into my office.
I've got work to do.

884
01:00:10,480 --> 01:00:13,711
I promise not to interrupt by calling
out points of passing interest...

885
01:00:13,880 --> 01:00:16,235
...or the weather conditions
over Baffin Bay.

886
01:00:16,400 --> 01:00:19,517
I'll see you in New York.
Don't forget to fasten your seat belt.

887
01:00:23,120 --> 01:00:24,439
[DOOR CLOSES]

888
01:00:24,600 --> 01:00:27,512
LOUISA: <i>What was wrong</i>
<i>with my hat anyway?</i>

889
01:00:30,720 --> 01:00:32,995
Okay, Mark, I'll take it.

890
01:00:33,600 --> 01:00:35,158
Okay, sir.

891
01:00:35,360 --> 01:00:37,669
LOUISA:
<i>I wondered who Melissa was</i>.

892
01:00:37,880 --> 01:00:40,872
<i>Some forgotten Hollywood starlet,</i>
<i>no doubt</i>.

893
01:00:41,680 --> 01:00:44,831
[PLANE ENGINE WHIRRING]

894
01:00:47,720 --> 01:00:51,679
<i>I was scared. I hated being alone</i>
<i>during the takeoff</i>.

895
01:01:22,080 --> 01:01:23,354
[PLANE ENGINE ROARING]

896
01:01:43,760 --> 01:01:45,432
<i>It was so beautiful looking down</i>.

897
01:01:47,240 --> 01:01:50,789
<i>The lights, the sky, the stars</i>.

898
01:01:52,200 --> 01:01:54,589
<i>How I wished I had someone</i>
<i>to share it with</i>.

899
01:01:54,800 --> 01:01:59,555
<i>Not this unsmiling, airborne,</i>
<i>cigar-store Indian</i>.

900
01:02:00,920 --> 01:02:02,751
<i>Then the fatal thing happened</i>.

901
01:02:08,920 --> 01:02:10,831
I'm glad you decided to join me.

902
01:02:11,880 --> 01:02:14,758
Nice to have someone
to share it with, isn't it?

903
01:02:16,720 --> 01:02:18,153
Beautiful.

904
01:02:19,320 --> 01:02:22,517
Excuse me, sir, telephone. Zurich.

905
01:02:23,080 --> 01:02:26,709
Willard, tell the gentleman
I just stepped out.

906
01:02:40,760 --> 01:02:43,228
LOUISA:
<i>I never did get to the St. Regis</i>.

907
01:02:43,400 --> 01:02:46,756
<i>We were married in New York,</i>
<i>in his fabulous penthouse</i>.

908
01:02:54,480 --> 01:02:55,959
[PHONE RINGING]

909
01:02:59,480 --> 01:03:01,232
Thank you, Timothy.

910
01:03:01,800 --> 01:03:03,233
Hello.

911
01:03:03,720 --> 01:03:05,119
Yes.

912
01:03:07,840 --> 01:03:09,353
Okay.

913
01:03:10,720 --> 01:03:12,995
LOUISA:
<i>I felt so safe at last</i>.

914
01:03:13,160 --> 01:03:17,233
<i>Rod had all the wealth and success</i>
<i>he wanted long before he met me</i>.

915
01:03:17,440 --> 01:03:21,035
<i>I felt I couldn't possibly jinx</i>
<i>his life</i>.

916
01:03:23,680 --> 01:03:25,432
<i>As for the mysterious Melissa</i>...

917
01:03:25,600 --> 01:03:27,670
...<i>I decided never</i>
<i>to question him about it</i>.

918
01:03:27,880 --> 01:03:30,348
<i>I dismissed it from my life</i>.

919
01:03:36,280 --> 01:03:38,840
ROD:
A little trinket from Harry Winston.

920
01:03:39,760 --> 01:03:41,352
LOUISA:
<i>As I look back on it now</i>...

921
01:03:41,520 --> 01:03:44,956
...<i>our life together was like one of</i>
<i>those glamorous Hollywood movies</i>...

922
01:03:45,120 --> 01:03:48,590
...<i>all about love</i>
<i>and what will she wear next?</i>

923
01:04:18,120 --> 01:04:21,590
Remind me to tell you later
that I love you.

924
01:04:24,800 --> 01:04:27,553
I'll remind you, if you'll remind me.

925
01:05:48,240 --> 01:05:50,879
- Louisa.
- Hello, Doris.

926
01:05:51,040 --> 01:05:53,873
- Now, Louisa, you look divine.
- Thank you.

927
01:05:58,240 --> 01:06:01,789
- You remember Peter, don't you?
- Oh, but of course.

928
01:06:05,040 --> 01:06:07,429
We met at El Morocco
the other evening.

929
01:06:07,640 --> 01:06:10,074
You play beautifully.
So nice of you to come.

930
01:06:10,240 --> 01:06:12,231
Thank you.
That's a beautiful dress.

931
01:06:12,440 --> 01:06:14,271
I'm glad you like it.

932
01:06:14,480 --> 01:06:18,996
It's my favorite.
My very own favorite.

933
01:06:19,920 --> 01:06:21,717
I want to talk to you.

934
01:06:21,920 --> 01:06:23,194
LOUISA:
What is it, dear?

935
01:06:23,360 --> 01:06:26,477
You remind me to tell you later
that I love you.

936
01:06:26,680 --> 01:06:29,433
- NICKY: Rod.
- Nicky.

937
01:06:31,600 --> 01:06:33,272
ROD:
Louisa.

938
01:06:36,320 --> 01:06:38,959
Louisa, darling, here is someone
you simply must meet.

939
01:06:47,040 --> 01:06:48,917
Darling, now you know
Nicky Cathcart.

940
01:06:49,120 --> 01:06:50,872
- Wonderful to meet you.
- Mrs. Cathcart.

941
01:06:51,040 --> 01:06:52,439
- How do you do?
- Louisa.

942
01:06:52,600 --> 01:06:55,194
I do hope the two of you can
come down to us for a shoot.

943
01:06:55,400 --> 01:06:58,392
Love to. We always get
a bang out of a shoot.

944
01:07:00,160 --> 01:07:02,958
Remind me to tell you...

945
01:07:03,320 --> 01:07:05,038
...that I...

946
01:07:05,560 --> 01:07:08,074
...love you.

947
01:07:24,080 --> 01:07:27,629
I'll remind you just as soon
as I change my nightgown.

948
01:07:36,360 --> 01:07:40,353
Lord Kensington, Lady Kensington,
may I present my wife, Louisa?

949
01:07:40,520 --> 01:07:42,351
- How do you do?
- So nice.

950
01:07:42,520 --> 01:07:44,078
- Delighted.
- How do you do?

951
01:07:44,240 --> 01:07:46,754
We're so happy you could
fly in for the evening.

952
01:07:46,920 --> 01:07:49,832
I hope the two of you can come down
to the abbey this weekend.

953
01:07:50,000 --> 01:07:51,479
We'd love to.

954
01:07:51,640 --> 01:07:54,234
Oh, but, darling,
I haven't a thing to wear.

955
01:07:57,520 --> 01:08:00,557
I'm reminding you to remind me
to tell you that I love you.

956
01:08:00,720 --> 01:08:02,915
Thank you for reminding me.

957
01:08:04,440 --> 01:08:05,793
I'm reminding you...

958
01:08:05,960 --> 01:08:09,236
...that you said to remind me
to tell me that you love me.

959
01:08:09,400 --> 01:08:11,675
Thank you for reminding me.

960
01:08:12,400 --> 01:08:13,913
Thank you.

961
01:08:19,360 --> 01:08:22,557
- I love you.
- I love you.

962
01:09:00,600 --> 01:09:02,989
- ROD: Why didn't he tell me before?
- Hello, darling.

963
01:09:03,160 --> 01:09:05,799
- I'm sorry I'm late.
- You tell him that he's through.

964
01:09:05,960 --> 01:09:09,509
This is total disaster.
How could it possibly happen to me?

965
01:09:09,720 --> 01:09:10,994
What happened?

966
01:09:11,160 --> 01:09:14,311
Louisa, ever since we got married,
I've been neglecting my business.

967
01:09:14,480 --> 01:09:17,313
I've been so in love with you
that I paid no attention to it.

968
01:09:17,480 --> 01:09:18,879
I just let it slide.

969
01:09:19,080 --> 01:09:21,878
Well, I've just been reading
these business reports.

970
01:09:22,040 --> 01:09:23,837
Are you faced with ruin?

971
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:27,117
I am three times as rich
as I was the day we got married.

972
01:09:27,320 --> 01:09:28,992
Oh, no.

973
01:09:29,160 --> 01:09:31,754
Nobody triples the business
of Anderson Enterprises...

974
01:09:31,920 --> 01:09:35,390
...but Rod Anderson.
Someone has been giving orders.

975
01:09:35,600 --> 01:09:37,989
Somewhere, somebody
in my organization.

976
01:09:38,160 --> 01:09:39,639
Why, that's absolute treachery!

977
01:09:39,800 --> 01:09:43,429
Someone's been giving orders
behind my back. Imagine that?

978
01:09:43,600 --> 01:09:46,319
If I want to lose a fortune,
I'll lose a fortune.

979
01:09:46,480 --> 01:09:50,359
If I want to triple it,
I'll triple it, no one else.

980
01:09:51,040 --> 01:09:53,554
I'm gonna get to every one
of my offices...

981
01:09:53,720 --> 01:09:56,188
...and find out who's running things
behind my back.

982
01:09:56,720 --> 01:10:00,269
Triple it. How could he possibly
triple it? Who can the guy be?

983
01:10:00,480 --> 01:10:02,710
You spend years training
employees, executives...

984
01:10:02,880 --> 01:10:06,839
...to serve you faithfully,
and they stab you behind the back.

985
01:10:07,720 --> 01:10:10,837
That's loyalty for you. Willard.

986
01:10:11,160 --> 01:10:15,153
Willard, you make arrangements
for trips to Sydney, Johannesburg...

987
01:10:15,360 --> 01:10:16,998
...Hong Kong and Bombay.

988
01:10:17,160 --> 01:10:20,596
I'm looking for somebody,
and I'm not coming back until I find him.

989
01:10:20,760 --> 01:10:22,751
LOUISA:
<i>I knew there was no man to look for</i>.

990
01:10:22,920 --> 01:10:25,036
<i>It was only me</i>
<i>and my witch's curse</i>.

991
01:10:26,600 --> 01:10:27,919
<i>Sleep was impossible</i>.

992
01:10:28,080 --> 01:10:30,469
<i>Next morning, Rod</i>
<i>would go out of my life forever</i>...

993
01:10:30,640 --> 01:10:32,710
...<i>and meet his doom somewhere</i>.

994
01:10:32,880 --> 01:10:36,759
<i>I was terrified. I tried</i>
<i>to think of a way to save him</i>.

995
01:10:45,920 --> 01:10:49,959
<i>"Melissa. Happy days</i>
<i>on his uncle's farm. "</i>

996
01:10:50,560 --> 01:10:52,630
<i>The simple life</i>.

997
01:11:05,120 --> 01:11:07,190
[MOOING]

998
01:11:12,360 --> 01:11:14,032
Melissa?

999
01:11:14,760 --> 01:11:17,752
Melissa.

1000
01:11:19,800 --> 01:11:20,949
[COCKEREL CROWING]

1001
01:11:27,800 --> 01:11:30,189
LOUISA:
<i>We had a simple, modest little farm</i>.

1002
01:11:30,400 --> 01:11:32,914
<i>Two dozens Leghorns</i>
<i>for me to look after</i>.

1003
01:11:33,080 --> 01:11:35,833
<i>And a cow named Melissa,</i>
<i>Melissa II</i>...

1004
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:38,195
...<i>and a bull named Melrose</i>.

1005
01:11:40,160 --> 01:11:43,152
Well, Ma, how do I look?
Neighbors all say I look real fine.

1006
01:11:44,120 --> 01:11:45,997
Wonderful, Pa, real elegant.

1007
01:11:46,200 --> 01:11:48,668
Have one more nip
of our local cider.

1008
01:11:48,840 --> 01:11:52,515
It's my fourth. I'm not a drinking man,
but seeing as how it's welcoming day...

1009
01:11:52,720 --> 01:11:54,358
...here's to you.
MAN 1: Thank you.

1010
01:11:54,560 --> 01:11:56,437
Good day, Mr. Anderson.

1011
01:11:56,600 --> 01:11:59,034
- Good day, Mrs. Anderson.
- Have another drink.

1012
01:11:59,240 --> 01:12:01,356
No, I'm driving.

1013
01:12:03,760 --> 01:12:06,320
- We'll see you, Rod.
- MAN 2: Come on, get him up.

1014
01:12:06,520 --> 01:12:09,159
- Come on, let's get him in the wagon.
- Come on, let's go.

1015
01:12:09,320 --> 01:12:12,949
MAN 1: No more.
MAN 3: Goodbye, Mr. Anderson.

1016
01:12:15,560 --> 01:12:18,154
I'm sure glad I listened to you.

1017
01:12:18,960 --> 01:12:20,871
This is our first day here
and already...

1018
01:12:21,080 --> 01:12:23,878
...I realize that this is what
I wanted to come back to.

1019
01:12:24,080 --> 01:12:26,310
And you made me do it.

1020
01:12:26,480 --> 01:12:27,708
[COW MOOS]

1021
01:12:27,920 --> 01:12:30,309
Uh-oh. Feeding time.

1022
01:12:31,240 --> 01:12:34,277
I'll go feed Melissa
and you milk the chickens, huh?

1023
01:12:34,480 --> 01:12:37,790
- I've waited a lot of years for that.
- Can't it wait till tomorrow?

1024
01:12:37,960 --> 01:12:39,712
Shows how much you know
about farming.

1025
01:12:39,880 --> 01:12:43,350
You don't milk her now,
and she'll be... mooing all night long.

1026
01:12:43,520 --> 01:12:45,078
Let's go.

1027
01:12:57,160 --> 01:13:00,038
Hello, Melissa, baby.

1028
01:13:04,840 --> 01:13:08,230
- How you doing, honey?
- Just great, honey.

1029
01:13:08,400 --> 01:13:11,198
That's a girl, Melissa, baby.

1030
01:13:13,520 --> 01:13:16,717
Whoa, baby. Whoa, Melissa.

1031
01:13:17,000 --> 01:13:19,195
That's a girl.

1032
01:13:19,360 --> 01:13:20,554
[BULL MOOS]

1033
01:13:20,720 --> 01:13:24,269
Melrose, forgive me!

1034
01:13:43,080 --> 01:13:45,514
"All the rest of my holdings, cash
and securities"...

1035
01:13:45,680 --> 01:13:47,432
LOUISA:
<i>Several months after the funeral</i>...

1036
01:13:47,600 --> 01:13:49,795
...<i>I had to listen</i>
<i>to the grim business details</i>.

1037
01:13:49,960 --> 01:13:51,916
<i>Rod had sold out everything</i>
<i>so quickly</i>...

1038
01:13:52,080 --> 01:13:54,116
...<i>that his fortune</i>
<i>was pitifully reduced</i>.

1039
01:13:54,280 --> 01:13:56,794
<i>It came to a mere $ 150 million</i>.

1040
01:13:57,640 --> 01:14:00,154
<i>I felt alone and lost</i>.
<i>And I was determined</i>...

1041
01:14:00,320 --> 01:14:04,950
...<i>to live alone for the rest of my life</i>.
<i>It was the only fair thing to do</i>.

1042
01:14:27,880 --> 01:14:30,758
Isn't there any way
of getting a cup of coffee here?

1043
01:14:30,960 --> 01:14:34,589
SINGS: <i>Isn't there any way</i>
<i>Of getting a cup of coffee here?</i>

1044
01:14:34,840 --> 01:14:39,868
- What's your name, Miss?
- Louisa May Hop... Hop...

1045
01:14:40,520 --> 01:14:44,399
Hop... Fli... Anderson.

1046
01:14:44,640 --> 01:14:47,598
SINGING: <i>Isn't there any way</i>
<i>Of getting a cup of coffee here?</i>

1047
01:14:47,760 --> 01:14:51,309
<i>Asks Louisa May Hop</i>
<i>Hop Hop Fli Anderson</i>

1048
01:14:51,480 --> 01:14:54,836
<i>Pretty eyes, pretty hair</i>
<i>And she asks so clear</i>

1049
01:14:55,000 --> 01:14:59,198
<i>Isn't there any way</i>
<i>Of getting a cup of coffee here?</i>

1050
01:15:04,000 --> 01:15:06,434
Louisa May Hop Hop
Hop Fli Anderson, huh?

1051
01:15:06,600 --> 01:15:08,591
That's a funny name.

1052
01:15:09,800 --> 01:15:12,030
It's just Anderson.

1053
01:15:14,240 --> 01:15:16,231
Please stay, Miss Anderson.

1054
01:15:16,440 --> 01:15:18,510
I'll get you a cup of coffee.

1055
01:15:18,840 --> 01:15:22,435
Clancy must be out back somewhere.
I'm in here all the time.

1056
01:15:23,280 --> 01:15:24,759
Say...

1057
01:15:24,960 --> 01:15:27,110
...I hope you didn't think
I was being fresh.

1058
01:15:27,320 --> 01:15:29,151
That's just part of my act,
you know.

1059
01:15:29,360 --> 01:15:31,999
I get a list of the customers' names
before the show...

1060
01:15:32,160 --> 01:15:34,879
...and then I make up little rhymes
using all their names.

1061
01:15:35,040 --> 01:15:37,508
It's one of my specialties.
That ad-lib stuff.

1062
01:15:37,720 --> 01:15:39,312
Coffee.

1063
01:15:39,600 --> 01:15:41,238
Sugar.

1064
01:15:41,640 --> 01:15:44,234
Danish? Serve the Danish.

1065
01:15:45,600 --> 01:15:48,194
And for a big finale, a napkin.

1066
01:15:48,400 --> 01:15:50,755
There's our Pinky, always at it.

1067
01:15:50,920 --> 01:15:52,751
Pinky, ain't you ever off the floor?

1068
01:15:52,920 --> 01:15:55,070
Why, it's Herman Bodkin,
I do declare...

1069
01:15:55,280 --> 01:15:57,350
...and Ernie Wilkens
who's with him there.

1070
01:15:57,520 --> 01:16:00,592
I said with a grin,
Ernie, your hair is getting thin.

1071
01:16:00,760 --> 01:16:03,832
And Ernie answered,
"Who wants fat hair?"

1072
01:16:06,920 --> 01:16:10,037
Oh, it's true.
I never seem to stop being on.

1073
01:16:10,240 --> 01:16:12,151
Oh, I liked it.

1074
01:16:13,080 --> 01:16:15,116
Are you performing around here?

1075
01:16:15,320 --> 01:16:18,676
Am I performing around here?

1076
01:16:19,760 --> 01:16:21,193
Look.

1077
01:16:24,120 --> 01:16:26,076
That's me, Pinky Benson.

1078
01:16:27,400 --> 01:16:30,551
Can I get you anything else?
It's on me.

1079
01:16:30,760 --> 01:16:32,512
No, thank you.

1080
01:16:33,200 --> 01:16:35,555
- What's doing?
- I got it, Clance.

1081
01:16:35,800 --> 01:16:37,153
LOUISA:
Thank you.

1082
01:16:37,360 --> 01:16:38,952
Say...

1083
01:16:39,120 --> 01:16:42,112
...if you're not busy later,
would you like to watch my act?

1084
01:16:42,480 --> 01:16:44,550
LOUISA:
<i>I hadn't decided what to do later</i>.

1085
01:16:44,720 --> 01:16:47,280
<i>I even thought of staying</i>
<i>in this town for a few days</i>...

1086
01:16:47,440 --> 01:16:49,158
...<i>till I made up my mind</i>.

1087
01:16:49,320 --> 01:16:50,594
Well?

1088
01:16:52,680 --> 01:16:55,592
Well, uh...

1089
01:16:56,720 --> 01:16:58,870
- Well, sure. I'll come.
- Good.

1090
01:16:59,520 --> 01:17:01,351
I gotta rush over there right now.

1091
01:17:01,520 --> 01:17:04,796
It takes me two hours to put
on my costume and makeup.

1092
01:17:04,960 --> 01:17:05,949
- Oh, really?
- Yeah.

1093
01:17:06,120 --> 01:17:07,394
How's it going?

1094
01:17:07,560 --> 01:17:12,076
Well, the management must love me.
I've been playing there for 14 years.

1095
01:17:14,520 --> 01:17:16,192
See you later.

1096
01:17:21,960 --> 01:17:24,076
Who ordered the well-done,
green-pea succotash?

1097
01:17:24,240 --> 01:17:26,231
- Here, over here.
- MAN 1: Medium-well.

1098
01:17:26,400 --> 01:17:29,119
- WAITER: Side of spinach.
- I ordered the creamed spinach.

1099
01:17:29,280 --> 01:17:33,751
That's better for you. No cholesterol.
Mashed potatoes, well-done.

1100
01:17:33,960 --> 01:17:38,351
- One rare hash brown.
- I ordered french fries. Take it back.

1101
01:17:38,560 --> 01:17:40,630
- You always make such a fuss.
- Shut up!

1102
01:17:40,800 --> 01:17:46,033
I agree. But stuff yourself, honey.
No man wants a fistful of bones.

1103
01:17:46,320 --> 01:17:48,276
TRENTINO:
Okay. Okay.

1104
01:17:48,440 --> 01:17:51,432
Here he is for your dinner pleasure.

1105
01:17:51,600 --> 01:17:57,072
Jersey City's own Pinky Benson!

1106
01:18:02,040 --> 01:18:04,474
Well, good evening,
friends and neighbors.

1107
01:18:04,680 --> 01:18:06,796
Hey, who do we have here
with us tonight?

1108
01:18:07,000 --> 01:18:08,353
The Shimkins!

1109
01:18:08,520 --> 01:18:11,956
Rosie Shimkin was able
to get a ringside table.

1110
01:18:12,120 --> 01:18:15,157
She's wearing a rose in her hat.
And with her is her husband Matt.

1111
01:18:15,320 --> 01:18:16,912
And that is that.

1112
01:18:17,120 --> 01:18:19,429
Dennis Horner is sitting
over there in the corner.

1113
01:18:19,600 --> 01:18:23,275
Hiya, Dennis. And Peggy Norton.
Peggy Norton and her sister Min.

1114
01:18:23,440 --> 01:18:26,398
Chewing on those bones
like Rin Tin Tin.

1115
01:18:26,560 --> 01:18:29,279
So welcome all, welcome one.

1116
01:18:29,440 --> 01:18:32,352
Lend an ear and have some fun.

1117
01:18:33,880 --> 01:18:37,634
SINGING: <i>I think that you and I</i>
<i>Should get acquainted</i>

1118
01:18:37,800 --> 01:18:40,075
<i>I'll just come up to you</i>
<i>And ask your name</i>

1119
01:18:40,240 --> 01:18:43,152
What I say is, live
and leave me alone.

1120
01:18:43,320 --> 01:18:45,276
<i>I'll say, "Isn't the weather fine?</i>

1121
01:18:45,440 --> 01:18:49,399
<i>And aren't you really glad</i>
<i>So glad that you came?"</i>

1122
01:18:49,560 --> 01:18:53,269
<i>Then after you</i>
<i>And I become acquainted</i>

1123
01:18:53,440 --> 01:18:57,194
<i>I'll ask you if you'd like</i>
<i>To stay a while</i>

1124
01:18:57,400 --> 01:18:59,197
<i>You'll say you would</i>

1125
01:18:59,400 --> 01:19:02,551
<i>You'll give me a smile</i>
<i>Oh, goody-good</i>

1126
01:19:02,800 --> 01:19:08,716
<i>You'll make my evening worthwhile</i>
<i>Before our little rendezvous ends</i>

1127
01:19:09,080 --> 01:19:11,913
<i>We won't just be acquainted</i>

1128
01:19:12,560 --> 01:19:17,350
<i>We'll be the very</i>
<i>Very best of friends</i>

1129
01:19:39,040 --> 01:19:40,951
LOUISA: <i>I could see why</i>
<i>the management loved him</i>.

1130
01:19:41,360 --> 01:19:45,399
<i>He didn't interfere one bit</i>
<i>with the sale of food and liquor</i>.

1131
01:20:14,320 --> 01:20:16,550
<i>It was the worst act I'd ever seen</i>.

1132
01:20:16,760 --> 01:20:19,194
<i>Just looking at Pinky</i>
<i>made me want to cry</i>...

1133
01:20:19,400 --> 01:20:21,391
...<i>but he was so happy</i>
<i>and untroubled</i>.

1134
01:20:21,640 --> 01:20:23,949
And I feel at home here,
as you can see.

1135
01:20:24,120 --> 01:20:27,874
